\begin_layout Chapter
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In many areas of science and engineering,
 we encounter systems or phenomena that involve randomness or uncertainty.
 Instead of having fixed values,
 measurements might vary unpredictably.
 Mathematical objects called stochastic processes,
 or more generally random fields (as introduced in Chapter
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "chap:Probability"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

),
 are used to model such situations where values change randomly over time or space.
 Examples include variations in material properties or fluctuating forces acting on a structure.
 However,
 random fields can possess infinite complexity,
 therefore working directly with them can be very difficult.
 A powerful technique to simplify them is the Karhunen-Loève (KL) expansion 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Karhunen1947,Loeve1948"
literal "false"

\end_inset

,
 which is a central topic of this thesis (discussed in Chapter
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "chap:Karhunen-Loève-expansion"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

).
 The KL expansion represents a random field as a sum of specific,
 deterministic functions multiplied by random coefficients.
 These deterministic functions capture the main spatial patterns of the randomness,
 and the random coefficients capture the uncertainty in the magnitude of these patterns.
 A key property is that these random coefficients are uncorrelated (and for Gaussian fields,
 independent),
 which simplifies analysis.
 The KL expansion is considered optimal because it captures the most variance (randomness) of the field using the fewest terms in the sum,
 making it efficient for representing complex random behavior in a manageable way.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The core of finding the KL expansion involves solving a specific mathematical problem:
 finding the eigenfunctions 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{j}$
\end_inset

 and eigenvalues 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{j}$
\end_inset

 of an integral operator defined by the random field’s autocovariance function 
\begin_inset Formula $c(\boldsymbol{x},\boldsymbol{y})$
\end_inset

.
 This function describes how related the random values are at different points 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{y}$
\end_inset

.
 The problem we need to solve looks like this:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\int_{\mathcal{T}}c(\boldsymbol{x},\boldsymbol{y})\psi_{j}(\boldsymbol{y})d\boldsymbol{y}=\lambda_{j}\psi_{j}(\boldsymbol{x}),\quad\boldsymbol{x}\in\mathcal{T}.\label{eq:intro_integral_eigenproblem}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

This is known as an integral eigenvalue problem.
 Finding exact analytical solutions (
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{j}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{j}$
\end_inset

) is usually impossible except in very simple cases.
 Therefore,
 we need numerical methods to find approximate solutions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This thesis focuses on a practical numerical approach to compute the approximate KL expansion.
 The chosen method is the Galerkin method (detailed in Chapter
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "chap:Karhunen-Loève-expansion"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

).
 The Galerkin method transforms the difficult integral eigenvalue problem into a more standard matrix eigenvalue problem,
 which can be solved using computational linear algebra techniques.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To use the Galerkin method effectively,
 we need two key ingredients developed in the earlier parts of this thesis:
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
Basis Functions:

\series default
 The Galerkin method approximates the unknown eigenfunctions 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{j}$
\end_inset

 as combinations of known,
 simpler functions called basis functions.
 A good choice for these basis functions,
 especially when working on intervals,
 are orthogonal polynomials.
 Chapter
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "chap:Polynomials"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 introduces orthogonal polynomials,
 focusing on Legendre polynomials.
 It explains how they are constructed using recurrence relations and how they relate to Jacobi matrices.
 We also see how to adapt them for any finite interval 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle a,b\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 Using an orthonormal basis simplifies the Galerkin formulation.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
Numerical Integration:

\series default
 Setting up the matrix eigenvalue problem in the Galerkin method requires calculating several integrals involving the basis functions and the covariance function 
\begin_inset Formula $c(\boldsymbol{x},\boldsymbol{y})$
\end_inset

.
 Calculating these integrals accurately and efficiently is crucial.
 Gaussian quadrature is a very effective technique for numerical integration,
 especially when integrating polynomials or functions well-approximated by polynomials.
 Chapter
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "chap:Polynomials"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 also details Gaussian quadrature,
 showing how the necessary quadrature nodes (
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{j}$
\end_inset

) and weights (
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{j}$
\end_inset

) can be computed directly from the Jacobi matrix associated with the orthogonal polynomials using the Golub-Welsch algorithm 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "GolubWelsch1969"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 The efficiency and accuracy of this quadrature method are demonstrated in the numerical experiments at the end of Chapter
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "chap:Polynomials"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Therefore,
 this thesis builds a computational pipeline:
 We use the theory of orthogonal polynomials (Chapter
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "chap:Polynomials"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

) to generate basis functions (Legendre polynomials) and to construct efficient Gaussian quadrature rules (via Jacobi matrices and Golub-Welsch).
 We then use these tools within the Galerkin method (Chapter
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "chap:Karhunen-Loève-expansion"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

) to approximate the solution of the integral eigenvalue problem 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:intro_integral_eigenproblem"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 arising from the autocovariance function (introduced in Chapter
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "chap:Probability"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

).
 The result is a numerical approximation of the Karhunen-Loève expansion for a given random field.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The structure of this thesis follows this logical progression:
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Chapter
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "chap:Polynomials"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

:
 Provides the mathematical foundation related to orthogonal polynomials.
 Key topics include definitions,
 weighted inner products,
 the three-term recurrence relation,
 Jacobi matrices,
 Gaussian quadrature rules,
 the Golub-Welsch algorithm for computing nodes and weights,
 and the generalization of Legendre polynomials to arbitrary finite intervals.
 The end of this Chapter demonstrates the concepts through numerical examples.
 This includes generating polynomials,
 timing the quadrature rule computation,
 and testing the convergence of Gaussian quadrature for integrating different types of functions.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Chapter
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "chap:Probability"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

:
 Introduces the necessary concepts from probability theory to understand random fields.
 This covers 
\begin_inset Formula $L^{2}$
\end_inset

 space,
 basic probability definitions,
 random variables,
 stochastic processes,
 random fields,
 expectation,
 covariance,
 autocovariance functions,
 and Gaussian random fields (GRF).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Chapter
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "chap:Karhunen-Loève-expansion"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

:
 Focuses on the Karhunen-Loève expansion itself.
 It presents the KL theorem and explains how to approximate the required eigenvalues and eigenfunctions using the Galerkin method with orthogonal polynomial basis functions.
 The role of Gaussian quadrature in computing the resulting integrals is emphasized.
 Numerical experiments show the computed KL components and their accuracy.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Chapter
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "chap:Conclusion"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

:
 Briefly summarizes the work presented and the results obtained.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
By following these steps,
 this thesis aims to provide a clear description and practical implementation of methods used to compute the Karhunen-Loève expansion,
 relying heavily on the properties of orthogonal polynomials and associated numerical techniques.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Chapter
Polynomials
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "chap:Polynomials"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This section is devoted to introduction of orthogonal polynomials with respect to given inner products.
 The inner products considered throughout this work are defined via integration over a specified interval 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 with respect to a continuous weight function 
\begin_inset Formula $w\in C(I)$
\end_inset

.
 A key characteristic of orthogonal polynomials with respect to these inner products,
 and by extension their normalized counterparts (orthonormal polynomials),
 is that they satisfy a three-term recurrence relation.
 The coefficients of this recurrence relation can be arranged into a symmetric tridiagonal matrix,
 known as the Jacobi matrix.
 The eigenpairs of this Jacobi matrix provide a direct method for determining the roots of the orthogonal polynomials.
 The chapter concludes with a discussion on Gaussian quadrature rules,
 which utilize the roots of orthogonal polynomials as nodes and derived values as weights for numerical integration.
 The eigenvalue (spectral) decomposition of the aforementioned Jacobi matrix yields,
 via Golub-Welsch algorithm 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "GolubWelsch1969"
literal "false"

\end_inset

,
 these quadrature nodes and weights.
 For Legendre polynomials,
 we also show how to extend them over a finite interval with the use of a simple affine transformation of variables.
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Furthermore,
 the specific case leading to Legendre polynomials is examined,
 corresponding to integration over an interval 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle a,b\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 with a unity weight function,
 
\begin_inset Formula $w(x)=1$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The section is organized as follows.
 Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Polynomials-of-real"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 introduces monic polynomials.
 Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Weighted-Inner-product"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 defines the weighted inner product and the orthonormal basis.
 Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Three-term-recurrence"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 presents the definition of Jacobi matrix derived from the three-term recurrence.
 Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Quadrature-rules"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 introduces the quadrature rule for approximating integrals over finite intervals.
 Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Golub-Welsch-algorithm"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 describes the Golub-Welsch algorithm for computing quadrature nodes and weights.
 Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Generalization-of-Legendre"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 focuses on Legendre polynomials and their affine generalizations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Standard results from linear algebra and functional analysis are used freely;
 key references for orthogonal polynomials are 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Gautschi2004,Szego1975,Chihara2011"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Polynomials of real variable
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Polynomials-of-real"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The scope of this study is confined to polynomials with real coefficients and of a real variable.
 A polynomial is considered as monic if its leading coefficient is equal to one.
 Specifically,
 a polynomial 
\begin_inset Formula $p(x)=a_{n}x^{n}+a_{n-1}x^{n-1}+\dots+a_{1}x+a_{0}$
\end_inset

 of degree 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 is monic if 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{n}=1$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Space of Polynomials
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "def:polynomials-of-degree"

\end_inset

For a non-negative integer 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

,
 let us define 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
P_{d}\coloneqq\left\{ p(x)=\sum_{i=0}^{d}a_{i}x^{i}\;\Big|\;a_{i}\in\mathbb{R}\right\} 
\]

\end_inset

as the space of real polynomials of degree at most 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

.
 The space of all real polynomials is then
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
P\coloneqq\bigcup_{d=0}^{\infty}P_{d}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Monic polynomials
\end_layout

\end_inset

For a non-negative integer 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

,
 let us define 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
P_{d}^{m}\coloneqq\left\{ \pi(x)=x^{d}+\sum_{i=0}^{d-1}a_{i}x^{i}\;\Big|\;a_{i}\in\mathbb{R}\right\} 
\]

\end_inset

as the set of 
\emph on
monic polynomials
\emph default
 of degree exactly 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Weighted Inner product
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Weighted-Inner-product"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this thesis we constraint ourselves to continuous weight functions,
 instead of the more general approach considering general measures as in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Gautschi2004"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 To define a weighted inner product properly,
 we first define a strictly positive continuous weight function 
\begin_inset Formula $w(x)$
\end_inset

 on a closed interval and the related symmetric bilinear form,
 denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle \cdot,\cdot\right\rangle _{w}$
\end_inset

.
 It is demonstrated that this form is positive definite,
 i.e.,
 it is a weighted inner product.
 For clarity and conciseness in the subsequent parts,
 the primary focus will be restricted to the specific case defined over the interval 
\begin_inset Formula $I=\left\langle -1,1\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 with the unity weight function 
\begin_inset Formula $w(x)=1$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Weight Function
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "def:weigh-function"

\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $I=\left\langle a,b\right\rangle \subset\mathbb{R},b>a$
\end_inset

 (a bounded,
 closed interval).
 A function 
\begin_inset Formula $w(x)\in C(I)$
\end_inset

 that satisfies 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\forall x\in I:w(x)>0,
\]

\end_inset

is called a 
\emph on
weight function
\emph default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Remark
The weighted integral is well defined for all 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in C(I)$
\end_inset

:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\intop_{I}f(x)w(x)\,dx\in\mathbb{R}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Moments of a Weight Function
\end_layout

\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $w(x),I$
\end_inset

 be a weight function and corresponding support.
 Then all moments are finite:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mu_{r}\coloneqq\intop_{I}x^{r}w(x)\,dx\in\mathbb{R},\;r=0,1,2,\ldots.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Weighted bilinear form
\end_layout

\end_inset

For a weight function 
\begin_inset Formula $w(x)$
\end_inset

 and its corresponding support 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

,
 we define the symmetric bilinear form 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle \cdot,\cdot\right\rangle _{w}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $u,v\in C(I)$
\end_inset

 as:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left\langle u,v\right\rangle _{w}=\intop_{I}u(x)v(x)w(x)\,dx.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Můžu to nazvat Norm?
 Ai říká že prý ne,
 protože to není ještě inner product
\end_layout

\end_inset

The operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\Vert u\right\Vert _{w}:C\left(I\right)\rightarrow\mathbb{R}_{0}^{+}$
\end_inset

,
 derived from the bilinear form 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle \cdot,\cdot\right\rangle _{w}$
\end_inset

,
 is defined as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left\Vert u\right\Vert _{w}=\sqrt{\left\langle u,u\right\rangle _{w}}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Positive definiteness
\end_layout

\end_inset

A bilinear form 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle \cdot,\cdot\right\rangle _{w}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $C\left(I\right)$
\end_inset

 is said to be positive definite if 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left\Vert u\right\Vert _{w}>0,\quad\forall u\in C\left(I\right):u\not\equiv0.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Lemma
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Inner product over 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle -1,1\right\rangle $
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "Inner-product-over-<-1,1>"

\end_inset

A symmetric bilinear form 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle \cdot,\cdot\right\rangle _{w}$
\end_inset

 with the weight function 
\begin_inset Formula $w(x)=1$
\end_inset

 and corresponding support 
\begin_inset Formula $I=\left\langle -1,1\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left\langle u,v\right\rangle _{w}=\intop_{-1}^{1}u(x)v(x)\,dx
\]

\end_inset

is positive definite on 
\begin_inset Formula $C\left(I\right)$
\end_inset

 ,
 i.e.
 it is an inner product.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $u\in C\left(\left\langle -1,1\right\rangle \right)$
\end_inset

 be a nonzero function,
 that is,
 
\begin_inset Formula $u\not\equiv0$
\end_inset

.
 Then,
 there exists some point 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0}\in\left\langle -1,1\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $u(x_{0})\neq0$
\end_inset

.
 Without loss of generality,
 assume 
\begin_inset Formula $u(x_{0})>0$
\end_inset

 (if 
\begin_inset Formula $u(x_{0})<0$
\end_inset

,
 consider 
\begin_inset Formula $-u$
\end_inset

 instead).
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Proof
Since 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 is continuous at 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0}$
\end_inset

,
 for the choice 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\epsilon=\frac{u(x_{0})}{2}>0,
\]

\end_inset

there exists a 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta>0$
\end_inset

 such that for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $|x-x_{0}|<\delta$
\end_inset

 (and 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\left\langle -1,1\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 ),
 we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
|u(x)-u(x_{0})|<\epsilon.
\]

\end_inset

This implies that for every 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 in the interval 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{\delta}=\left(x_{0}-\delta,x_{0}+\delta\right)\cap\left\langle -1,1\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 ,
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
u(x)>u(x_{0})-\epsilon=\frac{u(x_{0})}{2}>0.
\]

\end_inset

Thus,
 on 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{\delta}$
\end_inset

,
 we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
u(x)^{2}\ge\left(\frac{u(x_{0})}{2}\right)^{2}.
\]

\end_inset

Integrating over 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{\delta}$
\end_inset

 yields 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\intop_{I_{\delta}}u(x)^{2}\,dx\ge\intop_{I_{\delta}}\left(\frac{u(x_{0})}{2}\right)^{2}dx=\left(\frac{u(x_{0})}{2}\right)^{2}\cdot\left|I_{\delta}\right|,
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|I_{\delta}\right|$
\end_inset

 denotes the length of 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{\delta}$
\end_inset

,
 which is positive.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Since 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\|u\|_{w}^{2}=\intop_{-1}^{1}u(x)^{2}\,dx\ge\intop_{I_{\delta}}u(x)^{2}\,dx,
\]

\end_inset

it follows that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\|u\|_{w}^{2}\ge\left(\frac{u(x_{0})}{2}\right)^{2}\cdot\left|I_{\delta}\right|>0.
\]

\end_inset

Hence,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\|u\|_{w}>0$
\end_inset

 for every nonzero function 
\begin_inset Formula $u\in C\left(\left\langle -1,1\right\rangle \right)$
\end_inset

,
 and so the inner product is positive definite on 
\begin_inset Formula $C\left(\left\langle -1,1\right\rangle \right)$
\end_inset

 and thus on 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\varepsilon=\frac{u(x_{0})}{2}>0.
\]

\end_inset

Since 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 is continuous,
 for this 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon$
\end_inset

,
 there exists a 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta>0$
\end_inset

 such that for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 in the interval 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{\delta}=\left(x_{0}-\delta,x_{0}+\delta\right)\cap\left\langle -1,1\right\rangle $
\end_inset

,
 we have:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left|u(x)-u(x_{0})\right|<\varepsilon.
\]

\end_inset

Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{\delta}$
\end_inset

 has positive length 
\begin_inset Formula $|I_{\delta}|\geq\min\left(\delta,1\right)>0$
\end_inset

.
 Then,
 for every 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in I_{\delta}$
\end_inset

,
 it follows that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
u(x)>u(x_{0})-\varepsilon=\frac{u(x_{0})}{2}>0.
\]

\end_inset

This implies that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
u(x)^{2}>\left(\frac{u(x_{0})}{2}\right)^{2}.
\]

\end_inset

Integrating both sides over the interval 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{\delta}$
\end_inset

,
 we get:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\intop_{I_{\delta}}u(x)^{2}\,dx\ge\intop_{I_{\delta}}\left(\frac{u(x_{0})}{2}\right)^{2}dx=\left(\frac{u(x_{0})}{2}\right)^{2}\cdot\left|I_{\delta}\right|,
\]

\end_inset

The squared norm 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\Vert u\right\Vert _{w}^{2}$
\end_inset

 satisfies
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left\Vert u\right\Vert _{w}^{2}=\intop_{I}u(x)^{2}\,dx\ge\intop_{I_{\delta}}u(x)^{2}\,dx,
\]

\end_inset

therefore 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left\Vert u\right\Vert _{w}^{2}\ge\left(\frac{u(x_{0})}{2}\right)^{2}\cdot\left|I_{\delta}\right|>0.
\]

\end_inset

This shows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\Vert u\right\Vert _{w}>0$
\end_inset

 for every nonzero function 
\begin_inset Formula $u\in C\left(\left\langle -1,1\right\rangle \right)$
\end_inset

,
 and so the inner product is positive definite on 
\begin_inset Formula $C\left(\left\langle -1,1\right\rangle \right)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Corollary
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
to Lemma 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "Inner-product-over-<-1,1>"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\end_inset

Bilinear form 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle \cdot,\cdot\right\rangle _{w}$
\end_inset

 is an inner product for all 
\begin_inset Formula $w(x)$
\end_inset

 from Definition 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "def:weigh-function"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\nospellcheck off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\xout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none

\begin_inset Formula $\left\Vert \cdot\right\Vert _{w}$
\end_inset

 is a norm on 
\begin_inset Formula $C\left(I\right)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Remark
If 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle u,v\right\rangle _{w}=0$
\end_inset

,
 then 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 are said to be 
\emph on
orthogonal
\emph default
 with respect to the inner product 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle \cdot,\cdot\right\rangle _{w}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Shift Property
\end_layout

\end_inset

The inner product 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle \cdot,\cdot\right\rangle _{w}$
\end_inset

 has the property:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left\langle xu,v\right\rangle _{w}=\left\langle u,xv\right\rangle _{w},\quad\forall u,v\in P_{d}\quad\forall x\in\mathbb{R}.
\]

\end_inset

i.e.,
 we say it has the 
\emph on
shift property
\emph default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
The shift property holds for an inner product defined by weighted integrals:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left\langle xu,v\right\rangle _{w}=\intop_{I}\left(xu(x)\right)v(x)w(x)\,dx=\intop_{I}u(x)\left(xv(x)\right)w(x)\,dx=\left\langle u,xv\right\rangle _{w}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Normalized polynomials
\end_layout

\end_inset

For a non-negative integer 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

,
 the set of normalized polynomials with respect to the inner product 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle \cdot,\cdot\right\rangle _{w}$
\end_inset

 and norm 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\Vert \cdot\right\Vert _{w}$
\end_inset

 is defined as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\widetilde{P_{d}}\coloneqq\left\{ \tilde{p}\in P_{d}:\left\Vert \tilde{p}\right\Vert _{w}=1\right\} .
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Given the definition of the weighted inner product 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle \cdot,\cdot\right\rangle _{w}$
\end_inset

,
 a key objective is the construction of a corresponding sequence of orthogonal polynomials.
 A fundamental theorem guarantees that for such inner product defined on the space of polynomials,
 there exists an infinite sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \pi_{k}(x)\right\} _{k=0}^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 of polynomials such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle \pi_{j},\pi_{k}\right\rangle _{w}=0$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $j\neq k$
\end_inset

.
 Furthermore,
 this sequence can be uniquely determined by imposing the additional constraint that each polynomial 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{k}(x)$
\end_inset

 is monic.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
[Adapted from Gautchi,
 Theorem 1.6,
 p.3]
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after "Theorem 1.6"
key "Gautschi2004"
literal "false"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle \cdot,\cdot\right\rangle _{w}$
\end_inset

 be inner product on 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

,
 then there exists a unique infinite sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \pi_{k}\right\} _{k=0}^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 of monic orthogonal polynomials.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Three-term recurrence
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Three-term-recurrence"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For any inner product 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle \cdot,\cdot\right\rangle _{w}$
\end_inset

,
 there exists a basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \pi_{k}\right\} _{k=0}^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 for the polynomial space consisting of mutually orthogonal polynomials.
 Leveraging the properties of integral inner product,
 specifically the shift property,
 allows for the derivation of the three-term recurrence relation for these orthogonal polynomials.
 The coefficients of this recurrence relation also form a symmetric tridiagonal matrix,
 commonly referred to as the Jacobi matrix associated with the polynomial sequence.
 Crucially,
 the spectral decomposition of Jacobi matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $J_{n}$
\end_inset

 provides essential information:
 its eigenvalues correspond precisely to the roots of the 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-th orthogonal (and orthonormal) polynomial,
 and its eigenvectors are the previous orthonormal polynomials evaluated at these roots.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Three term recurrence
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after "Theorem 1.27"
key "Gautschi2004"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
[Adapted from Gautchi,
 Theorem 1.27,
 p.10]
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "thm:3-term-recurrence"

\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{k},k=0,1,2,\ldots$
\end_inset

,
 be monic orthogonal polynomials with respect to the inner product 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle \cdot,\cdot\right\rangle _{w}$
\end_inset

.
 Then,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\pi_{k+1}(x)=\left(x-\alpha_{k}\right)\pi_{k}(x)-\beta_{k}\pi_{k-1}(x),\quad k=0,1,2,\ldots,
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\pi_{-1}(x)=0,\pi_{0}(x)=1,
\]

\end_inset

where
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\alpha_{k}=\frac{\left\langle x\pi_{k},\pi_{k}\right\rangle _{w}}{\left\langle \pi_{k},\pi_{k}\right\rangle _{w}},\quad k=0,1,2,\ldots,
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\beta_{k}=\frac{\left\langle \pi_{k},\pi_{k}\right\rangle _{w}}{\left\langle \pi_{k-1},\pi_{k-1}\right\rangle _{w}},\quad k=1,2,\ldots,
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\beta_{0}=\left\langle \pi_{0},\pi_{0}\right\rangle _{w}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
We are going to generate a sequence of orthogonal polynomials 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \pi_{k}(x)\right\} $
\end_inset

 using a Gram-Schmidt process:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\pi_{0}(x) & = & f_{0}(x)\\
\pi_{1}(x) & = & f_{1}(x)-\frac{\left\langle f_{1},\pi_{0}\right\rangle _{w}}{\left\langle \pi_{0},\pi_{0}\right\rangle _{w}}\pi_{0}(x)\\
 & \vdots\\
\pi_{k}(x) & = & f_{k}(x)-\sum_{i=1}^{k-1}\frac{\left\langle f_{k},\pi_{i}\right\rangle _{w}}{\left\langle \pi_{i},\pi_{i}\right\rangle _{w}}\pi_{i}(x);
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

with 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{0}(x)=1$
\end_inset

 and each subsequent function to be orthogonalized is constructed as 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{k+1}(x)=x\pi_{k}(x)$
\end_inset

.
 Note that by this construction 
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\nospellcheck off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\xout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none

\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{k}$
\end_inset

 are monic and orthogonal polynomials.

\family default
\series default
\shape default
\size default
\emph default
\nospellcheck default
\bar default
\strikeout default
\xout default
\uuline default
\uwave default
\noun default
\color inherit
 In the 
\begin_inset Formula $k+1$
\end_inset

-th step 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{k+1}(x)$
\end_inset

 is orthogonalized against the subspace spanned by 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \pi_{0},\ldots,\pi_{k}\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 The polynomial 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{k+1}(x)$
\end_inset

 can then be represented as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\pi_{k+1}(x) & = & x\pi_{k}(x)-\sum_{i=1}^{k}\frac{\left\langle x\pi_{k},\pi_{i}\right\rangle _{w}}{\left\langle \pi_{i},\pi_{i}\right\rangle _{w}}\pi_{i}(x).
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

Expanding the sum,
 we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\pi_{k+1}(x)=x\pi_{k}(x)-\frac{\left\langle x\pi_{k},\pi_{k}\right\rangle _{w}}{\left\langle \pi_{k},\pi_{k}\right\rangle _{w}}\pi_{k}(x)-\frac{\left\langle x\pi_{k},\pi_{k-1}\right\rangle _{w}}{\left\langle \pi_{k-1},\pi_{k-1}\right\rangle _{w}}\pi_{k-1}(x)-\sum_{i=0}^{k-2}\frac{\left\langle x\pi_{k},\pi_{i}\right\rangle _{w}}{\left\langle \pi_{i},\pi_{i}\right\rangle _{w}}\pi_{i}(x).\label{eq:Expanded_Gram-Schmidt}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

By the shift property of the inner product,
 we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\forall k,i\in\mathbb{N}:\left\langle x\pi_{k},\pi_{i}\right\rangle _{w}=\left\langle \pi_{k},x\pi_{i}\right\rangle _{w}.
\]

\end_inset

Since 
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\nospellcheck off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\xout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none

\begin_inset Formula $x\pi_{i}$
\end_inset

 is a polynomial of degree 
\begin_inset Formula $i+1$
\end_inset

,

\family default
\series default
\shape default
\size default
\emph default
\nospellcheck default
\bar default
\strikeout default
\xout default
\uuline default
\uwave default
\noun default
\color inherit
 i.e.
 we can express 
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\nospellcheck off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\xout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none

\begin_inset Formula $x\pi_{i}\in P_{i+1}$
\end_inset

 as a linear combination of the orthogonal polynomials up to degree 
\family default
\series default
\shape default
\size default
\emph default
\nospellcheck default
\bar default
\strikeout default
\xout default
\uuline default
\uwave default
\noun default
\color inherit

\begin_inset Formula $i+1$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
x\pi_{i}(x)=\sum_{j=0}^{i+1}c_{j}\pi_{j}(x),\label{eq:Linear combination xpi_i+1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

for certain constants 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{j}$
\end_inset

.
 Then for 
\begin_inset Formula $k>i+1$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle \pi_{k},x\pi_{i}\right\rangle _{w}$
\end_inset

 is zero due to the orthogonality of the polynomials:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left\langle x\pi_{k},\pi_{i}\right\rangle _{w}=\left\langle \pi_{k},x\pi_{i}\right\rangle _{w}=\sum_{j=0}^{i+1}c_{j}\left\langle \pi_{k},\pi_{j}\right\rangle _{w}=0,\quad\forall k>i+1.
\]

\end_inset

This leads to the simplification of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:Expanded_Gram-Schmidt"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\pi_{k+1}(x)=x\pi_{k}(x)-\frac{\left\langle x\pi_{k},\pi_{k}\right\rangle _{w}}{\left\langle \pi_{k},\pi_{k}\right\rangle _{w}}\pi_{k}(x)-\frac{\left\langle x\pi_{k},\pi_{k-1}\right\rangle _{w}}{\left\langle \pi_{k-1},\pi_{k-1}\right\rangle _{w}}\pi_{k-1}(x),
\]

\end_inset

which simplifies further to
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\pi_{k+1}(x)=\left(x-\frac{\left\langle x\pi_{k},\pi_{k}\right\rangle _{w}}{\left\langle \pi_{k},\pi_{k}\right\rangle _{w}}\right)\pi_{k}(x)-\frac{\left\langle \pi_{k},\pi_{k}\right\rangle _{w}}{\left\langle \pi_{k-1},\pi_{k-1}\right\rangle _{w}}\pi_{k-1}(x).
\]

\end_inset

Which yields 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{k}=\frac{\left\langle x\pi_{k},\pi_{k}\right\rangle _{w}}{\left\langle \pi_{k},\pi_{k}\right\rangle _{w}}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $k=0,1,\ldots$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{0}=\left\langle \pi_{0},\pi_{0}\right\rangle _{w}$
\end_inset

,
 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{k}=\frac{\left\langle \pi_{k},\pi_{k}\right\rangle _{w}}{\left\langle \pi_{k-1},\pi_{k-1}\right\rangle _{w}}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $k=1,2,\ldots$
\end_inset

,
 i.e.
 we obtain the desired three-term recurrence relation:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\pi_{k+1}(x)=\left(x-\alpha_{k}\right)\pi_{k}(x)-\beta_{k}\pi_{k-1}(x).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Remark
Legendre polynomials 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{k}^{L}(x)$
\end_inset

 are orthogonal polynomials with respect to the standard inner product (weight 
\begin_inset Formula $w(x)=1$
\end_inset

) over the interval 
\begin_inset Formula $I^{L}=\left\langle -1,1\right\rangle $
\end_inset

.
 The coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{k}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{k}$
\end_inset

 for the three-term recurrence relation (Theorem 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "thm:3-term-recurrence"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

) for these monic orthogonal polynomials are given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{0}=2$
\end_inset

;
 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{k}=0$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $k=0,1,\ldots$
\end_inset

;

\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\nospellcheck off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\xout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none
 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{k}=1/(4−k^{−2})$
\end_inset


\family default
\series default
\shape default
\size default
\emph default
\nospellcheck default
\bar default
\strikeout default
\xout default
\uuline default
\uwave default
\noun default
\color inherit
 for 
\begin_inset Formula $k=1,2,\ldots$
\end_inset

 (see 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after "Table 1.1"
key "Gautschi2004"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Having a series of orthogonal polynomials and induced norm 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\Vert \cdot\right\Vert _{w}$
\end_inset

,
 we can form the orthonormal basis.
 Orthonormal basis can also be represented via three-term recurrence,
 tied to recurrence for monic polynomials.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after "Theorem 1.29"
key "Gautschi2004"
literal "false"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
[Adapted from Gautchi,
 Theorem 1.29,
 p.12]
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "thm:normal-3-term-recurrence"

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\pi}_{k}$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $k=0,1,2,\ldots,$
\end_inset

 be a series of orthonormal polynomials.
 Then,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sqrt{\beta_{k+1}}\tilde{\pi}_{k+1}(x)=\left(x-\alpha_{k}\right)\tilde{\pi}_{k}(x)-\sqrt{\beta_{k}}\tilde{\pi}_{k-1}(x),\quad k=0,1,2,\ldots,
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\tilde{\pi}_{-1}(x)=0,\quad\tilde{\pi}_{0}(x)=1/\sqrt{\beta_{0}},
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{k}$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{k}$
\end_inset

,
 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{0}$
\end_inset

 are defined in Theorem 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "thm:3-term-recurrence"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Monic orthogonal polynomials 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{k}$
\end_inset

 relate to the corresponding orthonormal polynomials 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\pi}_{k}$
\end_inset

 via 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{k}=\tilde{\pi}_{k}\left\Vert \pi_{k}\right\Vert _{w}$
\end_inset

,
 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\Vert \pi_{k}\right\Vert _{w}=\sqrt{\left\langle \pi_{k},\pi_{k}\right\rangle _{w}}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $k\in\mathbb{N}_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore,
 the three-term recurrence from Theorem 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "thm:3-term-recurrence"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 can be rewritten as:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\tilde{\pi}_{k+1}\sqrt{\left\langle \pi_{k+1},\pi_{k+1}\right\rangle _{w}} & = & \left(x-\alpha_{k}\right)\tilde{\pi}_{k}\sqrt{\left\langle \pi_{k},\pi_{k}\right\rangle _{w}}-\beta_{k}\tilde{\pi}_{k-1}\sqrt{\left\langle \pi_{k-1},\pi_{k-1}\right\rangle _{w}}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\tilde{\pi}_{k+1}\sqrt{\frac{\left\langle \pi_{k+1},\pi_{k+1}\right\rangle _{w}}{\left\langle \pi_{k},\pi_{k}\right\rangle _{w}}}=\left(x-\alpha_{k}\right)\tilde{\pi}_{k}-\beta_{k}\tilde{\pi}_{k-1}\sqrt{\frac{\left\langle \pi_{k-1},\pi_{k-1}\right\rangle _{w}}{\left\langle \pi_{k},\pi_{k}\right\rangle _{w}}}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\tilde{\pi}_{k+1}\sqrt{\beta_{k+1}}=\left(x-\alpha_{k}\right)\tilde{\pi}_{k}-\beta_{k}\tilde{\pi}_{k-1}\sqrt{\beta_{k}^{-1}}=\left(x-\alpha_{k}\right)\tilde{\pi}_{k}-\tilde{\pi}_{k-1}\sqrt{\beta_{k}}
\]

\end_inset

This gives us the three-term recurrence from Theorem 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "thm:normal-3-term-recurrence"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $k=1,2,\ldots$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Jacobi Matrix and it's eigenvalue decomposition
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The coefficients of three-term recurrence can be arranged into a three diagonal symmetric matrix.
 This matrix has useful ties to the recurrence itself yielding valuable ties between its eigenvalue decomposition and to the roots of orthogonal polynomials.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after "Definition 1.30"
key "Gautschi2004"
literal "false"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
[Adapted from Gautchi,
 Definition 1.30,
 p.13]
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

With reference to three term recurrence in Theorem 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "thm:normal-3-term-recurrence"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

,
 the 
\begin_inset Formula $n\times n$
\end_inset

 Jacobi matrix associated with the first 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 orthonormal polynomials is symmetric,
 tridiagonal matrix
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
J_{n}\coloneqq\begin{bmatrix}\alpha_{0} & \sqrt{\beta_{1}} &  &  & 0\\
\sqrt{\beta_{1}} & \alpha_{1} & \sqrt{\beta_{2}}\\
 & \sqrt{\beta_{2}} & \alpha_{2} & \ddots\\
 &  & \ddots & \ddots & \sqrt{\beta_{n}}\\
0 &  &  & \sqrt{\beta_{n}} & \alpha_{n}
\end{bmatrix}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Roots of monic polynomials
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after "Theorem 1.19"
key "Gautschi2004"
literal "false"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

The monic polynomial 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{n}\in P_{n}^{m}$
\end_inset

 of degree 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

,
 generated by the three-term recurrence relation from Theorem 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "thm:3-term-recurrence"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

,
 has exactly 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 unique real roots.
 We will denote these roots by 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\tau}^{(n)}=\left[\tau_{0}^{(n)},\ldots,\tau_{n-1}^{(n)}\right]$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The eigenvalue decomposition of the symmetric Jacobi matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $J_{n}$
\end_inset

 yields set of real eigenvalues.
 Specifically,
 if 
\begin_inset Formula $J_{n}$
\end_inset

 denotes the 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-th Jacobi matrix,
 its spectral decomposition is given by 
\begin_inset Formula $J_{n}=Q_{n}\Lambda_{n}Q_{n}^{T}$
\end_inset

,
 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda_{n}$
\end_inset

 is a diagonal matrix containing the real eigenvalues of 
\begin_inset Formula $J_{n}$
\end_inset

,
 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{n}$
\end_inset

 is an orthonormal matrix (
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{n}^{T}Q_{n}=Q_{n}Q_{n}^{T}=I$
\end_inset

) whose columns are the corresponding normalized eigenvectors.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For showing the ties between Jacobi matrix and orthonormal polynomials,
 we need to define a vector of orthonormal polynomials.
 For a sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\tilde{\pi}_{i}(x)\}_{i=0}^{n-1}$
\end_inset

 consisting of the first 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 orthonormal polynomials generated with respect to the inner product 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle \cdot,\cdot\right\rangle _{w}$
\end_inset

 (each polynomial 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\pi}_{i}(x),i=0,\ldots,n-1$
\end_inset

 has degree 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

) we define the corresponding vector of these orthonormal polynomials as:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\tilde{\boldsymbol{\pi}}(x)=\left[\tilde{\pi}_{0}(x),\tilde{\pi}_{1}(x),\ldots,\tilde{\pi}_{n-1}(x)\right]^{T}.
\]

\end_inset

This vector provides an orthonormal basis for the space of polynomials of degree at most 
\begin_inset Formula $n-1$
\end_inset

,
 denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{n-1}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after "Theorem 1.31"
key "Gautschi2004"
literal "false"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
[Adapted from Gautchi,
 Theorem 1.31,
 p.13]
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "thm:Jacobi-eigenvalues-eigenvectors"

\end_inset

The roots 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{j}^{(n)},j=0,1,\ldots,n-1,$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{n}$
\end_inset

 are the eigenvalues of the Jacobi matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $J_{n}$
\end_inset

.
 Furthermore,
 the vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\boldsymbol{\pi}}\left(\tau_{j}^{(n)}\right)$
\end_inset

 are corresponding eigenvectors,
 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\boldsymbol{\pi}}(x)=\left[\tilde{\pi}_{0}(x),\tilde{\pi}_{1}(x),\ldots,\tilde{\pi}_{n-1}(x)\right]^{T}$
\end_inset

,
 i.e.,
 for each 
\begin_inset Formula $j=0,1,\ldots,n-1$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\tau_{j}^{(n)}\tilde{\boldsymbol{\pi}}(\tau_{j}^{(n)})=J_{n}\tilde{\boldsymbol{\pi}}(\tau_{j}^{(n)}).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
If the first 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 equations from Theorem 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "thm:normal-3-term-recurrence"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 are written in the form 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x\tilde{\pi}_{k}(x)=\sqrt{\beta_{k}}\tilde{\pi}_{k-1}(x)+\alpha_{k}\tilde{\pi}_{k}(x)+\sqrt{\beta_{k+1}}\tilde{\pi}_{k+1}(x),\;k=0,1,\ldots,n-1,
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\tilde{\pi}_{-1}(x)=0,
\]

\end_inset

and we recall 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\tilde{\boldsymbol{\pi}}(x)=\left[\tilde{\pi}_{0}(x),\tilde{\pi}_{1}(x),\ldots,\tilde{\pi}_{n-1}(x)\right]^{T},
\]

\end_inset

then we can express these equations for 
\begin_inset Formula $k=0,1,\ldots n-1$
\end_inset

 in matrix form as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x\tilde{\boldsymbol{\pi}}(x)=J_{n}\tilde{\boldsymbol{\pi}}(x)+\sqrt{\beta_{n}}\tilde{\pi}_{n}(x)\boldsymbol{e}_{n},
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{e}_{n}=\left[0,0,\ldots,1\right]^{T}$
\end_inset

 is the 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-th coordinate vector in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 The assertions from Theorem 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "thm:Jacobi-eigenvalues-eigenvectors"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 regarding 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{j}^{(n)}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\boldsymbol{\pi}}\left(\tau_{j}^{(n)}\right)$
\end_inset

 follow immediately from this matrix equation by substituting 
\begin_inset Formula $x=\tau_{j}^{(n)}$
\end_inset

,
 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{j}^{(n)}$
\end_inset

 are roots of monic polynomial 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{n}$
\end_inset

 and noting that 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\boldsymbol{\pi}}(\tau_{j}^{(n)})\neq\boldsymbol{0}$
\end_inset

 (since its first component 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\pi}_{0}(\tau_{j}^{(n)})=1/\sqrt{\beta_{0}}\neq0$
\end_inset

),
 yields:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\tau_{j}^{(n)}\tilde{\boldsymbol{\pi}}(\tau_{j}^{i})=J_{n}\tilde{\boldsymbol{\pi}}(\tau_{j}^{(n)})+\sqrt{\beta_{n}}\tilde{\pi}_{n}(\tau_{j}^{(n)})e_{n}.
\]

\end_inset

Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{j}^{(n)}$
\end_inset

 are the roots of 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{n}$
\end_inset

,
 we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\pi}_{n}\left(\tau_{j}^{(n)}\right)=\pi_{i}\left(\tau_{j}^{(n)}\right)/\left\Vert \pi_{i}\right\Vert _{w}=0$
\end_inset

,
 and the equation simplifies to:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\tau_{j}^{(n)}\tilde{\boldsymbol{\pi}}(\tau_{j}^{(n)})=J_{n}\tilde{\boldsymbol{\pi}}(\tau_{j}^{(n)}).
\]

\end_inset

This shows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\tau_{j}^{(n)},\tilde{\boldsymbol{\pi}}(\tau_{j}^{(n)})\right)$
\end_inset

 are the eigenpairs of the Jacobi matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $J_{n}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Remark
Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\boldsymbol{\pi}}(\tau_{j}^{(n)})$
\end_inset

 are not necessarily normalized polynomials.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Corollary
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
to Theorem 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "thm:Jacobi-eigenvalues-eigenvectors"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after "Corollary to 1.31"
key "Gautschi2004"
literal "false"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
[Adapted from Gautchi,
 Corollary to 1.31,
 p.13]
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "cor:Cor to Jacobi eigen"

\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{v}_{j}^{(n)}$
\end_inset

 denote the normalized eigenvector of 
\begin_inset Formula $J_{n}$
\end_inset

 corresponding to the eigenvalue 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{j}^{(n)}$
\end_inset

,
 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{v}_{j,0}^{(n)}$
\end_inset

 denote its first component.
 These satisfy:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
J_{n}\boldsymbol{v}_{j}^{(n)}=\tau_{j}^{(n)}\boldsymbol{v}_{j}^{(n)},\quad\left(\boldsymbol{v}_{j}^{(n)}\right)^{T}\boldsymbol{v}_{j}^{(n)}=1.
\]

\end_inset

Then,
 for 
\begin_inset Formula $j=0,1,\ldots,n-1$
\end_inset

:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\beta_{0}\left(\boldsymbol{v}_{j,0}^{(n)}\right)^{2}=\frac{1}{\sum_{k=0}^{n-1}\left[\tilde{\pi}_{k}(\tau_{j}^{(n)})\right]^{2}}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Recall the vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\boldsymbol{\pi}}(x)=\left[\tilde{\pi}_{0}(x),\tilde{\pi}_{1}(x),\ldots,\tilde{\pi}_{n-1}(x)\right]$
\end_inset


\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\nospellcheck off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\xout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none
 from Theorem 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "thm:Jacobi-eigenvalues-eigenvectors"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.

\family default
\series default
\shape default
\size default
\emph default
\nospellcheck default
\bar default
\strikeout default
\xout default
\uuline default
\uwave default
\noun default
\color inherit
 For each normalized eigenvector 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{v}_{j}^{(n)}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\boldsymbol{v}_{j}^{(n)}=\left(\sum_{k=0}^{n-1}\left[\tilde{\pi}_{k}(\tau_{j}^{(n)})\right]^{2}\right)^{-1/2}\tilde{\boldsymbol{\pi}}(\tau_{j}^{(n)}),\quad j=0,1,\ldots,n.
\]

\end_inset

Noting from Theorem 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "thm:normal-3-term-recurrence"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 that 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\pi}_{0}=1/\sqrt{\beta_{0}}$
\end_inset

 is constant,
 if we compare the first component of each side of the vector equation above and square the resulting scalar equation,
 we obtain:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(\boldsymbol{v}_{j,0}^{(n)}\right)^{2}=\left(\sum_{k=0}^{n-1}\left[\tilde{\pi}_{k}(\tau_{j}^{(n)})\right]^{2}\right)^{-1}\frac{1}{\beta_{0}},\quad j=0,1,\ldots,n.
\]

\end_inset

Rearranging this gives the desired relationship:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\beta_{0}\left(\boldsymbol{v}_{j,0}^{(n)}\right)^{2}=\frac{1}{\sum_{k=0}^{n-1}\left[\tilde{\pi}_{k}(\tau_{j}^{(n)})\right]^{2}},\quad j=0,1,\ldots,n.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Quadrature rules
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Quadrature-rules"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Numerical quadrature provides an effective methodology for approximating the value of definite and improper integrals.
 The integral approximation is calculated as the weighted sum of the integrated function evaluated at the nodes.
 Specifically,
 Gaussian quadrature rules,
 which are intrinsically linked to orthogonal polynomials,
 offer high accuracy.
 This section introduces the process of deriving the quadrature nodes 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\tau_{i}\}_{i=1}^{N}$
\end_inset

 and corresponding weights 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\lambda_{i}\}_{i=1}^{N}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For more details on numerical approximation of integrals we refer to 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "DavisRabinowitz2007"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "StoerBulirsch2002"
literal "false"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The Quadrature rule
\end_layout

\end_inset

A quadrature rule is a set of weights 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{j}$
\end_inset

 and nodes 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{j}$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $j=1,2,\ldots,n$
\end_inset

,
 used to approximate the value of a weighted integral:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\intop_{I}f(x)w(x)\,dx\approx\sum_{j=1}^{n}\lambda_{j}f(\tau_{j}).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after "Theorem 1.45"
key "Gautschi2004"
literal "false"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
[Adapted from Gautchi,
 Theorem,
 1.45,
 p.21]
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

Consider a quadrature rule for approximating weighted integral 
\begin_inset Formula $\intop_{I}f(x)w(x)\,dx$
\end_inset

 using 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 distinct nodes 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{1},\ldots,\tau_{n}$
\end_inset

,
 where 
\begin_inset Formula $w(x)$
\end_inset

 is a positive weight function defining an inner product 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle \cdot,\cdot\right\rangle _{w}$
\end_inset

.
 Let this quadrature rule satisfy two conditions:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
1.
 The rule is interpolatory,
 meaning it is derived by integrating the Lagrange interpolating polynomial based on the nodes 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{j}$
\end_inset

.
 The approximation is given by:
 
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\nospellcheck off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\xout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none

\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\intop_{I}f(x)w(x)\,dx\approx\sum_{j=1}^{n}\lambda_{j}f(\tau_{j}),
\]

\end_inset


\family default
\series default
\shape default
\size default
\emph default
\nospellcheck default
\bar default
\strikeout default
\xout default
\uuline default
\uwave default
\noun default
\color inherit
where the weights 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{j}$
\end_inset

 are the integrals of the Lagrange basis polynomials:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\lambda_{j}=\intop_{I}l_{j}(x)w(x)\,dx,\label{eq:weights_of_quadrature}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $l_{j}(x)$
\end_inset

 are the Lagrange basis polynomials:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
l_{j}(x)=\prod_{\substack{\mu=1\\
\mu\neq j
}
}^{n}\frac{x-\tau_{\mu}}{\tau_{j}-\tau_{\mu}}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
2.
 The node polynomial 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{n}(x)=\prod_{j=1}^{n}(x-\tau_{j})$
\end_inset

,
 is orthogonal to all polynomials 
\begin_inset Formula $p(x)$
\end_inset

 of degree less than 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 with respect to the weight function 
\begin_inset Formula $w(x)$
\end_inset

.
 That is:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\intop_{I}w(x)\omega_{n}(x)p(x)\,dx=0,
\]

\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in P_{n-1}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
If both conditions hold,
 then the nodes 
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\nospellcheck off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\xout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none

\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{1},\ldots,\tau_{n}$
\end_inset


\family default
\series default
\shape default
\size default
\emph default
\nospellcheck default
\bar default
\strikeout default
\xout default
\uuline default
\uwave default
\noun default
\color inherit
 of the quadrature rule are precisely the roots of the 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-th degree orthogonal polynomial 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{n}(x)$
\end_inset

 associated with the weight function 
\begin_inset Formula $w(x)$
\end_inset

 and correspondingly the inner product 
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\nospellcheck off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\xout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none

\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle \cdot,\cdot\right\rangle _{w}$
\end_inset


\family default
\series default
\shape default
\size default
\emph default
\nospellcheck default
\bar default
\strikeout default
\xout default
\uuline default
\uwave default
\noun default
\color inherit
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Remark
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula $2n-1$
\end_inset

 quadrature exactness 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after "pg. 8"
key "Gautschi2004"
literal "false"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "rem:2n-1-quadrature-exactness"

\end_inset

The 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-point Gauss quadrature rule integrates polynomials of degree up to 
\begin_inset Formula $2n-1$
\end_inset

 exactly.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Golub-Welsch algorithm
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Golub-Welsch-algorithm"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Having established that the roots of the orthogonal polynomial 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{n}$
\end_inset

 correspond to the eigenvalues of the associated Jacobi matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $J_{n}$
\end_inset

,
 the focus now shifts to the computation of the corresponding quadrature weights.
 This section details the procedure for determining these weights,
 employing the well-established Golub-Welsch algorithm 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "GolubWelsch1969"
literal "false"

\end_inset

,
 which utilizes the first components of the normalized eigenvectors.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Gauss Quardature from eigenvectors
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "thm:Gauss-Quardature-from"

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after "Theorem 3.1"
key "Gautschi2004"
literal "false"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

The nodes 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{j}$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $j=1,2,\ldots,n$
\end_inset

,
 of the 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-point Gauss quadrature rule associated with the inner product 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle \cdot,\cdot\right\rangle _{w}$
\end_inset

 are the eigenvalues of the Jacobi matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $J_{n}$
\end_inset

.
 The corresponding weights 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{j},j=1,2,3,\ldots,n$
\end_inset

,
 are given by:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\lambda_{j}=\beta_{0}\boldsymbol{v}_{j,1}^{2},
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{0}=\int_{I}w(x)\,dx$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{v}_{j,1}$
\end_inset

 is the first component of the normalized eigenvector 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{v}_{j}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $J_{n}$
\end_inset

 corresponding to the eigenvalue 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{j}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after "page 153"
key "Gautschi2004"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 Let us recall a vector of orthonormal polynomials 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\tilde{\boldsymbol{\pi}}(x)=\left[\tilde{\pi}_{0}(x),\tilde{\pi}_{1}(x),\ldots,\tilde{\pi}_{n-1}(x)\right]^{T}.
\]

\end_inset

From Corollary 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "cor:Cor to Jacobi eigen"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 we have:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\beta_{0}\boldsymbol{v}_{j,1}^{2}=\frac{1}{\sum_{k=0}^{n-1}\left[\tilde{\pi}_{k}(\tau_{j}^{(n)})\right]^{2}},\quad j=1,\dots,n,
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{v}_{j,1}$
\end_inset

 is the first component of the normalized eigenvector 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{v}_{j}$
\end_inset

 corresponding to the eigenvalue 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{j}^{(n)}$
\end_inset

.
 Next,
 let 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)=\tilde{\pi}_{k}(x)$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $k\in\{0,1,\ldots,n-1\}$
\end_inset

.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-point Gauss quadrature rule integrates polynomials of degree up to 
\begin_inset Formula $2n-1$
\end_inset

 exactly,
 see Remark 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "rem:2n-1-quadrature-exactness"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 is a polynomial of degree 
\begin_inset Formula $k\le n-1<2n-1$
\end_inset

,
 the Gauss formula is exact:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\intop_{I}\tilde{\pi}_{k}(x)w(x)\,dx=\sum_{j=1}^{n}\lambda_{j}^{G}\tilde{\pi}_{k}(\tau_{j}^{G}),\quad k=0,1,\ldots,n-1.
\]

\end_inset

The integral on the left side is 
\begin_inset Formula $\intop_{I}\tilde{\pi}_{k}(x)w(x)\,dx=\langle\tilde{\pi}_{k},1\rangle_{w}$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $1=\sqrt{\beta_{0}}\tilde{\pi}_{0}(x)$
\end_inset

 (because 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\pi}_{0}$
\end_inset

 is the constant orthonormal polynomial,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\pi}_{0}=1/||\pi_{0}||_{w}=1/\sqrt{\langle1,1\rangle_{w}}=1/\sqrt{\beta_{0}}$
\end_inset

),
 this integral becomes 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{\beta_{0}}\langle\tilde{\pi}_{k},\tilde{\pi}_{0}\rangle_{w}=\sqrt{\beta_{0}}\delta_{k,0}$
\end_inset

 by the orthonormality of the 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\pi}$
\end_inset

 polynomials.
 Thus,
 the exact Gauss formula yields:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\beta_{0}^{1/2}\delta_{k,0}=\sum_{j=1}^{n}\lambda_{j}^{G}\tilde{\pi}_{k}(\tau_{j}^{G}),\quad k=0,1,\ldots,n-1,
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{k,0}$
\end_inset

 is the Kronecker delta.
 This system of equations can be written in matrix form as:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
P^{T}\boldsymbol{\lambda}^{G}=\beta_{0}^{1/2}\boldsymbol{e}_{1},\label{eq:Gauss_matrix_form}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 is the 
\begin_inset Formula $n\times n$
\end_inset

 matrix whose 
\begin_inset Formula $(k+1,j)$
\end_inset

 entry is 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\pi}_{k}(\tau_{j}^{G})$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\lambda}^{G}$
\end_inset

 is the vector of Gauss weights 
\begin_inset Formula $[\lambda_{1}^{G},\dots,\lambda_{n}^{G}]^{T}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{e}_{1}=\left[1,0,\ldots,0\right]^{T}\in\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 is the first standard basis vector.
 From Theorem 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "thm:Jacobi-eigenvalues-eigenvectors"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 we know that the columns of 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 are eigenvectors,
 therefore mutually orthogonal,
 and specifically:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
PP^{T}=D_{\pi}=\left[\begin{array}{cccc}
d_{0}\\
 & d_{1}\\
 &  & \ddots\\
 &  &  & d_{n-1}
\end{array}\right],\quad d_{j-1}=\sum_{k=0}^{n-1}\left[\tilde{\pi}_{k}(\tau_{j}^{(n)})\right]^{2}
\]

\end_inset

Multiplying the equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:Gauss_matrix_form"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 from the left yields:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
D_{\pi}\boldsymbol{\lambda}^{G}=\beta_{0}^{1/2}P\boldsymbol{e}_{1}.
\]

\end_inset

Since the first row of 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 consists of 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\pi}_{0}(\tau_{j}^{G})$
\end_inset

 and from Theorem 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "thm:normal-3-term-recurrence"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\pi}_{0}(x)=\beta_{0}^{-1/2}$
\end_inset

,
 then
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\beta_{0}^{1/2}P\boldsymbol{e}_{1}=\beta_{0}^{1/2}\beta_{0}^{-1/2}\boldsymbol{e}=\boldsymbol{e},
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{e}=\left[1,1,\ldots,1\right]^{T}\in\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 There follows 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda^{G}=D_{\pi}^{-1}\boldsymbol{e}$
\end_inset

,
 that is,
 for each 
\begin_inset Formula $j=1,\dots,n$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\lambda_{j}^{G}=\frac{1}{d_{j-1}}=\frac{1}{\sum_{k=0}^{n-1}\left[\tilde{\pi}_{k}(\tau_{j}^{(n)})\right]^{2}},
\]

\end_inset

by Corollary 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "cor:Cor to Jacobi eigen"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 yielding 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{j}^{G}=\beta_{0}\boldsymbol{v}_{j,1}^{2}.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Generalization of Legendre polynomials and quadrature 
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Generalization-of-Legendre"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This work focuses specifically on Legendre polynomials because they can be adapted for integration over any finite interval 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle a,b\right\rangle $
\end_inset

.
 Such integration can be achieved by applying an affine transformation to the Legendre polynomials and their corresponding quadrature nodes and weights.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Remark
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "rem:affine_generalization_of_Legendre"

\end_inset

Let the orthogonal polynomials denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{i}^{L}(x)$
\end_inset

 (the Legendre polynomials) be defined with respect to the inner product over the interval 
\begin_inset Formula $I^{L}=\left\langle -1,1\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 with the weight function 
\begin_inset Formula $w(x)=1$
\end_inset

.
 Consider an interval 
\begin_inset Formula $I=\left\langle a,b\right\rangle $
\end_inset

,
 where 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b\in\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $a<b$
\end_inset

.
 For the inner product defined over the interval 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 with the weight function 
\begin_inset Formula $w(x)=1$
\end_inset

,
 the corresponding orthogonal polynomials 
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\nospellcheck off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\xout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none

\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{i}(x)$
\end_inset


\family default
\series default
\shape default
\size default
\emph default
\nospellcheck default
\bar default
\strikeout default
\xout default
\uuline default
\uwave default
\noun default
\color inherit
 are related to 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{i}^{L}(x)$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{i}(x)=\pi_{i}^{L}\left(\frac{a+b}{a-b}+\frac{2}{b-a}x\right)\sqrt{\frac{2}{b-a}}.$
\end_inset

 Additionally,
 this transformation preserves the normalization of the basis,
 i.e.
 if 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\pi}_{i}^{L}$
\end_inset

 are the orthonormal Legendre polynomials,
 then the polynomials defined by 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\pi}_{i}(x)=\tilde{\pi}_{i}^{L}\left(\frac{a+b}{a-b}+\frac{2}{b-a}x\right)\sqrt{\frac{2}{b-a}}$
\end_inset

 are also orthonormal.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
We will prove the orthogonality of the polynomials 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{i}(x)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{j}(x)$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $i\neq j$
\end_inset

 with respect to the inner product 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle\cdot,\cdot\rangle_{1}=\int_{a}^{b}u(x)v(x)dx$
\end_inset

.
 Recall the relationship 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{k}(x)=\pi_{k}^{L}\left(\frac{a+b}{a-b}+\frac{2}{b-a}x\right)\sqrt{\frac{2}{b-a}}$
\end_inset

,
 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{k}^{L}$
\end_inset

 are Legendre polynomials.
 Thus,
 for 
\begin_inset Formula $i\neq j$
\end_inset

:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left\langle \pi_{i},\pi_{j}\right\rangle _{1}=\intop_{a}^{b}\pi_{i}(x)\pi_{j}(x)\,dx=\intop_{a}^{b}\pi_{i}^{L}\left(\frac{a+b}{a-b}+\frac{2}{b-a}x\right)\pi_{j}^{L}\left(\frac{a+b}{a-b}+\frac{2}{b-a}x\right)\frac{2}{b-a}\,dx.
\]

\end_inset

Let us perform the substitution:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\hat{x}=\frac{a+b}{a-b}+\frac{2}{b-a}x.
\]

\end_inset

Then 
\begin_inset Formula $d\hat{x}=\frac{2}{b-a}dx$
\end_inset

.
 The limits change as follows:
 when 
\begin_inset Formula $x=a$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{x}=-1$
\end_inset

,
 and when 
\begin_inset Formula $x=b$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{x}=1$
\end_inset

.
 Substituting into the integral gives:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\intop_{a}^{b}\pi_{i}^{L}\left(\dots\right)\pi_{j}^{L}\left(\dots\right)\,\frac{2}{b-a}dx & =\intop_{-1}^{1}\pi_{i}^{L}\left(\hat{x}\right)\pi_{j}^{L}\left(\hat{x}\right)\,d\hat{x}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{i}^{L}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{j}^{L}$
\end_inset

 are orthogonal Legendre polynomials for 
\begin_inset Formula $i\neq j$
\end_inset

 with respect to the weight 
\begin_inset Formula $w(x)=1$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $[-1,1]$
\end_inset

,
 the integral is zero:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\intop_{-1}^{1}\pi_{i}^{L}\left(\hat{x}\right)\pi_{j}^{L}\left(\hat{x}\right)\,d\hat{x}=0.
\]

\end_inset

Therefore,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle \pi_{i},\pi_{j}\right\rangle _{1}=0$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $i\neq j$
\end_inset

.
 If the polynomials 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{i}^{L}$
\end_inset

 are orthonormal then 
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\nospellcheck off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\xout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none

\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{i}$
\end_inset


\family default
\series default
\shape default
\size default
\emph default
\nospellcheck default
\bar default
\strikeout default
\xout default
\uuline default
\uwave default
\noun default
\color inherit
 are also orthonormal.
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Maybe I could prove it.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Also might need to be rewritten
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after "Theorem 1.47"
key "Gautschi2004"
literal "false"

\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "thm:quad_weights_equation"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

The weights 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{j}$
\end_inset

 for an 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-point quadrature rule approximating 
\begin_inset Formula $\intop_{a}^{b}f\left(x\right)w\left(x\right)\,dx$
\end_inset

,
 using the roots 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{i}$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $i=0,\dots,n-1$
\end_inset

) of the corresponding orthogonal polynomial as nodes (eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:weights_of_quadrature"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

),
 are given by:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\lambda_{j}=\frac{\intop_{a}^{b}\prod_{i\neq j,i=0}^{n-1}\left(x-\tau_{i}\right)\,dx}{\prod_{i\neq j,i=0}^{n-1}\left(\tau_{j}-\tau_{i}\right)},\quad j=0,\dots,n-1.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Remark
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "rem:affine-nodes-and-weights"

\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{i}^{L}$
\end_inset

 denote the roots of Lagrange polynomials and 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{i}^{L}$
\end_inset

 denote the corresponding Gauss-Legendre quadrature weights.
 For orthogonal polynomials 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(x)$
\end_inset

 associated with the inner product over the interval 
\begin_inset Formula $I=\left\langle a,b\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 (with weight 
\begin_inset Formula $w(x)=1$
\end_inset

),
 the roots (Gauss quadrature nodes) are 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{i}=\frac{a+b}{2}+\frac{b-a}{2}\tau_{i}^{L}$
\end_inset

 and the weights are 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{i}=\frac{b-a}{2}\lambda_{i}^{L}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{i}^{L}$
\end_inset

 be the roots of the 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-th degree Legendre polynomial 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{n}^{L}$
\end_inset

,
 then
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\nospellcheck off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\xout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none
 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi^{L}(\tau_{i}^{L})=0$
\end_inset


\family default
\series default
\shape default
\size default
\emph default
\nospellcheck default
\bar default
\strikeout default
\xout default
\uuline default
\uwave default
\noun default
\color inherit
 for all 
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\nospellcheck off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\xout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none

\begin_inset Formula $i=0,\ldots,n-1$
\end_inset

.
 From Remark 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "rem:affine_generalization_of_Legendre"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 we have the 
\family default
\series default
\shape default
\size default
\emph default
\nospellcheck default
\bar default
\strikeout default
\xout default
\uuline default
\uwave default
\noun default
\color inherit
polynomial
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\nospellcheck off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\xout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none
 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{n}(x)=\pi_{n}^{L}\left(\frac{a+b}{a-b}+\frac{2}{b-a}x\right)\sqrt{\frac{2}{b-a}}$
\end_inset


\family default
\series default
\shape default
\size default
\emph default
\nospellcheck default
\bar default
\strikeout default
\xout default
\uuline default
\uwave default
\noun default
\color inherit
.
 The roots 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{i}$
\end_inset

 of the polynomial 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{n}$
\end_inset

 must satisfy 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{n}(\tau_{i})=0$
\end_inset

.
 This implies:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\pi_{n}^{L}\left(\frac{a+b}{a-b}+\frac{2}{b-a}\tau_{i}\right)=0.
\]

\end_inset

Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{i}^{L}$
\end_inset

 are the roots of 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{n}^{L}$
\end_inset

,
 we must have:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\tau_{i}^{L}=\frac{a+b}{a-b}+\frac{2}{b-a}\tau_{i}\;\Longrightarrow\;\frac{a+b}{2}+\frac{b-a}{2}\tau_{i}^{L}=\tau_{i}.
\]

\end_inset


\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\nospellcheck off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\xout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none
 
\family default
\series default
\shape default
\size default
\emph default
\nospellcheck default
\bar default
\strikeout default
\xout default
\uuline default
\uwave default
\noun default
\color inherit
If we then utilize this substitution in Theorem 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "thm:quad_weights_equation"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 we get:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\lambda_{j} & = & \frac{\intop_{a}^{b}\prod_{i\neq j,i=0}^{n-1}\left(x-\tau_{i}\right)\,dx}{\prod_{i\neq j,i=0}^{n-1}\left(\tau_{j}-\tau_{i}\right)}=\\
 & = & \frac{\int_{a}^{b}\prod_{i\neq j,i=0}^{n-1}\left(x-\frac{a+b}{2}-\frac{b-a}{2}\tau_{i}^{L}\right)\,dx}{\prod_{i\neq j,i=0}^{n-1}\left(\frac{a+b}{2}+\frac{b-a}{2}\tau_{j}^{L}-\frac{a+b}{2}-\frac{b-a}{2}\tau_{i}^{L}\right)}=\\
 & = & \frac{\int_{-1}^{1}\frac{b-a}{2}\prod_{i\neq j,i=0}^{n-1}\left(\frac{a+b}{2}+\frac{b-a}{2}\hat{x}-\frac{a+b}{2}-\frac{b-a}{2}\tau_{i}^{L}\right)\,d\hat{x}}{\prod_{i\neq j,i=0}^{n-1}\left(\frac{b-a}{2}\left(\tau_{j}^{L}-\tau_{i}^{L}\right)\right)}=\\
 & = & \frac{\left(\frac{b-a}{2}\right)^{n}\int_{-1}^{1}\prod_{i\neq j,i=0}^{n-1}\left(\hat{x}-\tau_{i}^{L}\right)\,d\hat{x}}{\left(\frac{b-a}{2}\right)^{n-1}\prod_{i\neq j,i=0}^{n-1}\left(\tau_{j}^{L}-\tau_{i}^{L}\right)}=\\
 & = & \frac{b-a}{2}\,\frac{\int_{-1}^{1}\prod_{i\neq j,i=0}^{n-1}\left(\hat{x}-\tau_{i}^{L}\right)\,d\hat{x}}{\prod_{i\neq j,i=0}^{n-1}\left(\tau_{j}^{L}-\tau_{i}^{L}\right)}=\\
 & = & \frac{b-a}{2}\lambda_{j}^{L}.
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Numerical experiments
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
