\begin_layout Subsection
Quadrature rules
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The focus now shifts to Gaussian quadrature rules and their use for approximations of definite integrals over finite intervals.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
First,
 the computational time required to obtain the quadrature nodes and weights is examined.
 This computation involves determining the eigenpairs of the Jacobi matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $J_{n}$
\end_inset

 and its construction and is performed using the Golub-Welsch algorithm.
 The Jacobi matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $J_{n}$
\end_inset

 is represented in the code as two one-dimensional arrays:
 the main diagonal and the first sub-diagonal.
 These arrays are then used in a function `eigh_tridiagonal` from the `scipy.linalg` library to calculate the eigenvalues and eigenvectors.
 From Theorem 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "thm:Gauss-Quardature-from"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

,
 we know that the eigenvalues are the quadrature nodes and the weights can be obtained from the first components of the eigenvectors.
 Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Log-Log-Plot-of-Time"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 illustrates the relationship between the size 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 of the Jacobi matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $J_{n}$
\end_inset

 (where 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 is also the number of nodes and weights obtained) and the time taken to compute these nodes and weights.
 It is a log-log graph where we observe that the data points can be approximated by a linear fit with a slope close to 2,
 suggesting that the computation time has approximately quadratic complexity.
 
\begin_inset Float figure
placement document
alignment center
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename Graphs/NodesWightsTime.pdf

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Log-Log Plot of Computation Time vs.
 Jacobi Size 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:Log-Log-Plot-of-Time"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset

We will now try to experiment with different functions and examine the approximation error 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|i_{n}-i^{*}\right|$
\end_inset

,
 where 
\begin_inset Formula $i_{n}$
\end_inset

 is the integral approximation obtained using 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 nodes and weights,
 and 
\begin_inset Formula $i^{*}$
\end_inset

 is the exact value of the integral.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
We will approximate the integral of a polynomial.
 Specifically,
 we will consider the polynomial 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)=x^{50}+x^{4}-4x^{3}-15x+35$
\end_inset

.
 The exact value of the integral in this case will is 
\family roman
