\begin_layout Example
Here we experiment with an integral of a non-smooth function 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)=\left|x\right|+\left|x+0.5\right|-\left|x-0.5\right|$
\end_inset

.
 The exact value of the integral is 
\begin_inset Formula $i^{*}=1$
\end_inset

.
 Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Approximation-of-NonSmooth-Integ"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 shows this function and the corresponding quadrature approximation error for an increasing number of nodes.
 A noticeable pattern in the error can be observed:
 its value fluctuates depending on whether an odd or even number of nodes and weights is used.
 The overall accuracy of the approximation is also lower than typically achieved for smooth functions.
 This behavior is expected because the effectiveness of Gaussian quadrature depends on the smoothness of the function being integrated,
 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 has points where it is not differentiable within the interval 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

.
 In order to achieve a better approximation,
 we could split the interval 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 into multiple subintervals such that the function is smooth on each subinterval,
 and then integrate the function separately over each respective subinterval.
 Note that in this case a quadrature consisting of two points would be enough for each of the four subintervals.
