\begin_layout Chapter
Probability
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "chap:Probability"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This chapter starts with an introduction to the Hilbert space 
\begin_inset Formula $L^{2}(I)$
\end_inset

.
 To keep the thesis approachable,
 we constructed 
\begin_inset Formula $L^{2}(I)$
\end_inset

 as a completion of the space of continuous functions 
\begin_inset Formula $C(I)$
\end_inset

 with respect to the 
\begin_inset Formula $L^{2}$
\end_inset

 norm defined on the interval 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

.
 After this,
 key ideas from probability theory are introduced.
 This includes foundational elements of measure theory,
 the axiomatic definition of a probability space,
 and the concept of expected value.
 Building upon this foundation,
 the discussion then progresses to the topic of stochastic processes,
 introducing the concepts of random fields,
 their associated autocovariance functions,
 and the important subclass represented by Gaussian random fields (GRF).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For more details considering the basics of functional analysis and measure theory,
 please refer to 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Kreyszig1989,RoydenFitzpartick2010"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 More details on probability theory can be found in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "LordPowellShardlow2014,GrimmettStirzaker2001"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
\begin_inset Formula $L^{2}$
\end_inset

 space
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\nospellcheck off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\xout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none
\begin_inset Formula $L^{2}$
\end_inset


\family default
\series default
\shape default
\size default
\emph default
\nospellcheck default
\bar default
\strikeout default
\xout default
\uuline default
\uwave default
\noun default
\color inherit
 norm
\end_layout

\end_inset

For an interval 
\begin_inset Formula $I=\left\langle a,b\right\rangle ,$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b\in\mathbb{R},a<b$
\end_inset

,
 the 
\begin_inset Formula $L^{2}$
\end_inset

-norm on 
\begin_inset Formula $C\left(I\right)$
\end_inset

 is defined as
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\nospellcheck off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\xout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none

\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left\Vert f\right\Vert _{L^{2}}\coloneqq\left(\intop_{I}\left|f(x)\right|^{2}dx\right)^{1/2}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Cauchy sequence
\end_layout

\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ f_{i}\right\} _{i=0}^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 be a sequence of functions in 
\begin_inset Formula $C(I)$
\end_inset

,
 where 
\begin_inset Formula $I=\left\langle a,b\right\rangle $
\end_inset

.
 This sequence is called a Cauchy sequence with respect to the 
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\nospellcheck off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\xout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none

\begin_inset Formula $L^{2}$
\end_inset


\family default
\series default
\shape default
\size default
\emph default
\nospellcheck default
\bar default
\strikeout default
\xout default
\uuline default
\uwave default
\noun default
\color inherit
-norm 
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\nospellcheck off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\xout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none

\begin_inset Formula $\left\Vert \cdot\right\Vert _{L^{2}}$
\end_inset

,

\family default
\series default
\shape default
\size default
\emph default
\nospellcheck default
\bar default
\strikeout default
\xout default
\uuline default
\uwave default
\noun default
\color inherit
 if for every 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon>0$
\end_inset

 there exists an integer 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 such that for all integers 
\begin_inset Formula $m,n\geq N$
\end_inset

,
 we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left\Vert f_{n}-f_{m}\right\Vert _{L^{2}}<\varepsilon.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\nospellcheck off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\xout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}^{2}$
\end_inset

 set
\end_layout

\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}^{2}(I)$
\end_inset

 denote the set of all Cauchy sequences 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ f_{i}\right\} \subset C(I)$
\end_inset

 with respect to the 
\begin_inset Formula $L^{2}$
\end_inset

-norm.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Equivalence class
\end_layout

\end_inset

We call two Cauchy sequences 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ f_{i}\right\} ,\left\{ g_{i}\right\} \in\mathcal{L}^{2}(I)$
\end_inset

 equivalent if
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\lim_{i\rightarrow\infty}\left\Vert f_{i}-g_{i}\right\Vert _{L^{2}}=0.
\]

\end_inset

The set of all sequences equivalent to a given sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $\{f_{i}\}$
\end_inset

 is called an equivalence class and is denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[\left\{ f_{i}\right\} \right]$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\nospellcheck off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\xout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none
\begin_inset Formula $L^{2}$
\end_inset


\family default
\series default
\shape default
\size default
\emph default
\nospellcheck default
\bar default
\strikeout default
\xout default
\uuline default
\uwave default
\noun default
\color inherit
 Space
\end_layout

\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $F\coloneqq\left\{ f_{i}\right\} _{i=0}^{\infty}\in\mathcal{L}^{2}(I)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $G\coloneqq\left\{ g_{i}\right\} _{i=0}^{\infty}\in\mathcal{L}^{2}(I)$
\end_inset

.
 Let us define the space 
\begin_inset Formula $L^{2}(I)$
\end_inset

 as an equivalence class space on 
