LatexCommand cite
after "section 7.4 Theorem 12"
key "RoydenFitzpartick2010"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Probability fundamentals
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider a probability space 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\Omega,\mathcal{F},\mathbb{P}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

 is the sample space,
 i.e.
 it is the set of all possible outcomes.
 In general,
 the sample space is an abstract set,
 one large enough to parameterize all possible outcomes of the experiment.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 is a collection of subsets of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

 and comprises of those subsets to which we can assign probabilities.
 Formally,
 it is a 
\emph on

\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

-algebra
\emph default
.
 Any measurable set,
 
\begin_inset Formula $F\in\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 is known as an 
\emph on
event
\emph default
.
 Each event corresponds to a set of outcomes in the experiment.
 The probability measure 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}$
\end_inset

 assigns a probability,
 a number between 0 and 1,
 to every measurable set in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
We can consider rolls of dice as an example of probability space 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\Omega,\mathcal{F},\mathbb{P}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 In a roll of a die there are six possible outcomes and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega=\left\{ 1,2,3,4,5,6\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 For a sequence of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 rolls,
 the sample space is 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega=\left\{ 1,2,3,4,5,6\right\} ^{M}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 is a collection of subsets of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

,
 these subsets are known as events.
 Each event corresponds to a set of outcomes in the experiment.
 Let's say we want to know the probability of rolling an even number and so the set 
\begin_inset Formula $F=\left\{ 2,4,6\right\} $
\end_inset

 is included as an event in the 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

-algebra 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

.
 Lastly we have the probability measure 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}$
\end_inset

,
 which assigns a probability to every measurable set in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

.
 Probability will be a number between 0 and 1,
 where 0 means the even will never occur and one means the event will always occur.
 Higher probability means the event is more likely to occur in an experiment.
 For a fair dice roll the probability of rolling an even number would be 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}\left(\left\{ 2,4,6\right\} \right)=1/2$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

-algebra
\end_layout

\end_inset

For a set 
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\nospellcheck off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\xout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none

\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

,
 we call a set 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

,
 whose elements are subsets of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

,
 a sigma 
\family default
\series default
\shape default
\size default
\emph default
\nospellcheck default
\bar default
\strikeout default
\xout default
\uuline default
\uwave default
\noun default
\color inherit

\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

-
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\nospellcheck off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\xout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none
algebra if and only if it satisfies the following axioms:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
1.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega\in\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
2.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $A\in\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

,
 then 
\begin_inset Formula $A^{c}\in\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

(where 
\begin_inset Formula $A^{c}$
\end_inset

 is the complement of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

,
 also denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega\setminus A$
\end_inset

),
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
3.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ A_{n}\right\} $
\end_inset

 is a countable collection of elements of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $A=\bigcup_{n=1}^{\infty}A_{n}$
\end_inset

,
 then 
\begin_inset Formula $A\in\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

