\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

A measure 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $(\Omega,\mathcal{F})$
\end_inset

 is a 
\emph on
probability measure
\emph default
 if it has unit total mass,
 i.e.,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}(\Omega)=1$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Probability space
\end_layout

\end_inset

A probability space is a triple 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\Omega,\mathcal{F},\mathbb{P}\right)$
\end_inset

,
 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

 is a sample space,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 is a sigma-algebra of events and 
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\nospellcheck off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\xout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none

\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}$
\end_inset


\family default
\series default
\shape default
\size default
\emph default
\nospellcheck default
\bar default
\strikeout default
\xout default
\uuline default
\uwave default
\noun default
\color inherit
 is a probability measure on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Stochastic processes and random fields
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This section defines stochastic processes and random fields,
 we will work only with real-valued variables.
 Further on,
 we discuss the covariance and the autocovariance function.
 The section concludes by explaining the meaning of stationarity for a stochastic process.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Random variables,
 Realisation 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after "Definition 4.3"
key "LordPowellShardlow2014"
literal "false"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
[Adapted from Lord,
 Definition 4.3,
 p.138]
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

For a probability space 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\Omega,\mathcal{F},\mathbb{P}\right)$
\end_inset

,
 a measurable map 
\begin_inset Formula $X:\mathcal{F}\rightarrow\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 is called a real-valued 
\emph on
random variable
\emph default
.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Remark
The value 
\begin_inset Formula $X(\omega)$
\end_inset

 for a given outcome 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega\in\Omega$
\end_inset

 belongs to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 and is called a 
\emph on
realization
\emph default
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Random vector
\end_layout

\end_inset

A random vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{X}\coloneqq\left(X_{1},X_{2},\ldots,X_{n}\right)$
\end_inset

 is a vector whose elements 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{i},i=1,2,\ldots,n$
\end_inset

 are random variables.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Stochastic Process 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after "Definition 5.2"
key "LordPowellShardlow2014"
literal "false"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
[Adapted from Lord,
 Definition 5.2,
 p.182]
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

Given a set 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{T}\subset\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 and a probability space 
\begin_inset Formula $(\Omega,\mathcal{F},\mathbb{P})$
\end_inset

,
 a real-valued 
\emph on
stochastic process
\emph default
 (also known as a random process) is a collection of real-valued random variables 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ X(t):t\in\mathcal{T}\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 The stochastic process can also be viewed as a map 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega\rightarrow L^{2}\left(\mathcal{T}\right)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Random Field 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after "Definition 7.1"
key "LordPowellShardlow2014"
literal "false"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
[Adapted from Lord,
 Definition 7.2,
 p.258]
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

Given a set 
\begin_inset Formula $D\subset\mathbb{R}^{d}$
\end_inset

 and a probability space 
\begin_inset Formula $(\Omega,\mathcal{F},\mathbb{P})$
\end_inset

,
 a real-valued 
\emph on
random field
\emph default
 is a collection of real-valued random variables 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ u(\boldsymbol{x}):\boldsymbol{x}\in D\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 The random field can also be viewed as a map 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega\rightarrow L^{2}\left(D\right)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Expected Value
\end_layout

\end_inset

For a continuous random variable 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 with probability density function (PDF) 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

,
 the expected value is defined as:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbb{E}\left[X\right]\coloneqq\intop_{-\infty}^{\infty}xf\left(x\right)dx.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Covariance 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after "Definition 4.14"
key "LordPowellShardlow2014"
literal "false"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
[Adapted from Lord,
 Definition 4.14,
 p.142]
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

The covariance of two real-valued random variables 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Cov\left(X,Y\right)\coloneqq\mathbb{E}\left[\left(X-\mu_{X}\right)\left(Y-\mu_{Y}\right)\right]=\mathbb{E}\left[XY\right]-\mu_{X}\mu_{Y},
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{X}=\mathbb{E}\left[X\right]$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{Y}=\mathbb{E}\left[Y\right]$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Autocovariance function
\end_layout

\end_inset

The autocovariance function 
\begin_inset Formula $C\left(s,t\right)$
\end_inset

 of a stochastic process or random field 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ X\left(t\right):t\in\mathcal{T}\right\} $
\end_inset

 is defined as:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
C\left(s,t\right)\coloneqq\Cov\left(X\left(s\right),X\left(t\right)\right),
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $s,t\in\mathcal{T}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For simplicity we will assume that the expected value will be a constant zero function,
 i.e.,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{E}\left[X\right]=0$
\end_inset

.
 Note that if this is not the case,
 we can instead consider stochastic process 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ Y\left(t\right):t\in\mathcal{T}\right\} $
\end_inset

,
 where 
\begin_inset Formula $Y=X-\mathbb{E}\left[X\right]$
\end_inset

.
 Then the expected value of 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 would be zero.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Stationary process 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after "Definition 6.1"
key "LordPowellShardlow2014"
literal "false"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
[Adapted from Lord,
 Definition 6.1,
 p.217]
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

A stochastic process 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ X\left(t\right):t\in\mathcal{T}\right\} $
\end_inset

 is called stationary if its covariance function 
\begin_inset Formula $C\left(s,t\right)$
\end_inset

 depends only on the difference 
\begin_inset Formula $s-t$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The covariance function of a stationary stochastic process 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ X\left(t\right):t\in\mathcal{T}\right\} $
\end_inset

 can be written as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
C\left(s,t\right)=C\left(s-t,0\right)\eqqcolon c\left(s-t\right),
\]

\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $c\left(\tau\right)$
\end_inset

 is known as the stationary covariance function.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Isotropic Random Field 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after "Definition 7.14"
key "LordPowellShardlow2014"
literal "false"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
[Adapted from Lord,
 Definition 7.14,
 p.263]
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

A random field 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ X\left(\boldsymbol{x}\right):\boldsymbol{x}\in\mathbb{R}^{d}\right\} $
\end_inset

 is isotropic and stationary if its stationary covariance function 
\begin_inset Formula $c\left(\boldsymbol{x}\right)=c^{0}\left(r\right),$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $r\coloneqq\left\Vert \boldsymbol{x}\right\Vert _{2}$
\end_inset

,
 for a function 
\begin_inset Formula $c^{0}:\mathbb{R}^{+}\rightarrow\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 known as the isotropic covariance.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The main focus here will be random fields 
\begin_inset Formula $X(t)$
\end_inset

 with Gaussian distribution,
 i.e.
 Gaussian random fields (GRF).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Gaussian distribution
\end_layout

\end_inset

A random variable 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is said to have the Gaussian (or normal) distribution with mean 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu\in\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 and variance 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma^{2}>0$
\end_inset

,
 if its probability density function (PDF)
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
to do:
 define earlier
\end_layout

\end_inset

 is given by:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f\left(x\right)=\frac{1}{\sqrt{2\pi\sigma^{2}}}\exp\left(\frac{-\left(x-\mu\right)^{2}}{2\sigma^{2}}\right),\quad x\in\mathbb{R}.
\]

\end_inset

We denote this by 
\begin_inset Formula $X\sim N\left(\mu,\sigma^{2}\right)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Gaussian vector
\end_layout

\end_inset

A random vector 
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\nospellcheck off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\xout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none

\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{X}\coloneqq\left(X_{1},X_{2},\ldots,X_{n}\right)$
\end_inset


\family default
\series default
\shape default
\size default
\emph default
\nospellcheck default
\bar default
\strikeout default
\xout default
\uuline default
\uwave default
\noun default
\color inherit
 is said to be a Gaussian vector if there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu\in\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $A\in\mathbb{R}^{n\times m}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{X}=\mu+A\mathbb{Y}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Y}$
\end_inset

 is an 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

-dimensional random vector whose components are independent and have the Gaussian distribution.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Gaussian Random Field 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after "Definition 7.5"
key "LordPowellShardlow2014"
literal "false"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

A Gaussian random field (GRF) 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ u\left(\boldsymbol{x}\right):\boldsymbol{x}\in D\right\} $
\end_inset

 is a random field such that for any finite set of points 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}_{1},\ldots,\boldsymbol{x}_{n}\in D$
\end_inset

 (where 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

),
 the random vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{u}=\left[u(\boldsymbol{x}_{1}),u(\boldsymbol{x}_{2}),\ldots,u(\boldsymbol{x}_{n})\right]^{T}$
\end_inset

 follows the multivariate Gaussian (or normal) distribution.
 Specifically,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{u}\sim N\left(\boldsymbol{\mu},C\right)$
\end_inset

,
 where the mean vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\mu}$
\end_inset

 has components 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{i}=\mathbb{E}[u(\boldsymbol{x}_{i})]$
\end_inset

 and the covariance matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 has entries 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{ij}=\Cov\left(u(\boldsymbol{x}_{i}),u(\boldsymbol{x}_{j})\right)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Autocovariance functions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this section,
 we will examine some basic autocovariance functions.
 An original source introducing covariance functions as a tool for describing spacial properties of random field via a family of Matérn covariance functions is 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Matern1960"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Covariance-Functions"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 shows five different autocovariance functions.
 These include three Matérn covariance functions,
 each with a different smoothness parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset

.
 Also shown are the Squared Exponential (Gaussian) covariance function 
\begin_inset Formula $C(d)=e^{-\frac{d^{2}}{2}}$
\end_inset

 and the Exponential covariance function 
\begin_inset Formula $C(d)=e^{-d}$
\end_inset

.
 We note that the Matérn covariance function with 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu=0.5$
\end_inset

 is equivalent to the exponential covariance function.
 
\begin_inset Float figure
placement document
alignment document
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename Graphs/CovarienceFunctions.pdf

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Autocovariance Functions
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:Covariance-Functions"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Chapter
Karhunen-Loève expansion
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "chap:Karhunen-Loève-expansion"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This section addresses the Karhunen-Loève (KL) expansion 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Karhunen1947,Loeve1948"
literal "false"

\end_inset

,
 specifically focusing on its application to Isotropic GRF for which we will consider the expected value will be constant zero function,
 i.e.,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{E}\left[X\right]=0$
\end_inset

 .
 Subsequently,
 a numerical approximation of the KL expansion is computed using the Galerkin method.
 Gaussian quadrature techniques are employed for the efficient numerical evaluation of these integrals.
 The determination of the eigenfunctions and eigenvalues required for the KL expansion inherently corresponds to solving an integral eigenvalue problem,
 which is conceptually equivalent to the spectral decomposition of the covariance operator associated with the random field.
 The Galerkin procedure provides a means to discretize this problem,
 leading to a matrix eigenvalue problem.
 The main computational part of this method consists of integrals over the specified multi-dimensional domain 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{T}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For more details on KL decomposition and its numerical approximation,
 we refer the reader to 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "LordPowellShardlow2014,GhanemSpanos1991"
literal "false"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Karhunen-Loève
\end_layout

\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X(t)$
\end_inset

 be a zero mean Gaussian random field.
 We are interested in expressing the sample paths 
\begin_inset Formula $X(t,\omega)\in L^{2}\left(\mathcal{T}\right)$
\end_inset

 as a series in an orthonormal basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\tilde{\pi}_{j}:j\in\mathbb{N}\}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $L^{2}(\mathcal{T})$
\end_inset

.
 That is,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
X(t,\omega)=\sum_{j=1}^{\infty}\gamma_{j}(\omega)\sqrt{\lambda_{j}}\psi_{j}(t),\label{eq:Karhunen-Loeve}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where the coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{j}$
\end_inset

 are random variables defined by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\gamma_{j}(\omega)\coloneqq\langle X(t,\omega),\tilde{\pi}_{j}(t)\rangle_{L^{2}(\mathcal{T})}
\]

\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\lambda_{j},\psi_{j}\right)$
\end_inset

 are eigenpairs of the autocovariance operator 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left(Cu\right)\left(x\right)\coloneqq\intop_{\mathcal{T}}c\left(x,y\right)u\left(y\right)dy.\label{eq:covariance_operator}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Remark
The random variables 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{j}$
\end_inset

 have zero mean,
 unit variance and are pairwise uncorrelated.
 Moreover,
 for GRF they are independent.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Tensor space
\end_layout

\end_inset

Let us have an 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

-dimensional space 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{N}^{x}\coloneqq\spanSed\left\{ \psi_{1},\ldots,\psi_{N}\right\} $
\end_inset

 and an 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

-dimensional space 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{M}^{y}\coloneqq\spanSed\left\{ \phi_{1},\ldots,\phi_{M}\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 The tensor product space is defined as 
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\nospellcheck off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\xout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none

\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V_{N}^{x}\otimes V_{M}^{y}:=\spanSed\left\{ \psi_{i}\phi_{j}:i=1,\ldots,N,j=1,\ldots,M\right\} 
\]

\end_inset


\family default
\series default
\shape default
\size default
\emph default
\nospellcheck default
\bar default
\strikeout default
\xout default
\uuline default
\uwave default
\noun default
\color inherit
 and has dimension 
\begin_inset Formula $NM$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Remark
An 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

-dimensional tensor product space 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{N}^{x}$
\end_inset

 can be formed from 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 one-dimensional spaces 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{1}^{x_{i}}$
\end_inset

:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V_{N}^{x}=V_{1}^{x_{1}}\otimes V_{1}^{x_{2}}\otimes\cdots\otimes V_{1}^{x_{N}}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We want to approximate eigenpairs 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\lambda,u\right)$
\end_inset


\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\nospellcheck off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\xout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none
 of C,
 i.e.
 find 
\family default
\series default
\shape default
\size default
\emph default
\nospellcheck default
\bar default
\strikeout default
\xout default
\uuline default
\uwave default
\noun default
\color inherit

\begin_inset Formula $\left(\lambda_{i},u_{i}\right)$
\end_inset

 such
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\nospellcheck off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\xout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none

\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left(Cu_{i}\right)\left(\boldsymbol{x}\right)\coloneqq\intop_{\mathcal{T}}c\left(\boldsymbol{x},\boldsymbol{y}\right)u_{i}\left(\boldsymbol{y}\right)d\boldsymbol{y}=\lambda_{i}u_{i}\left(\boldsymbol{x}\right),\quad\forall\boldsymbol{x}\in\mathcal{T}.\label{eq:eigenproblem}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
The Galerkin method for approximation of eigenpairs of autocovariance operator
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Galerkin method is employed to compute approximations of the desired eigenpairs 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\lambda_{i},u_{i}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 the Galerkin approach discretizes the underlying operator eigenvalue problem,
 resulting in a matrix eigenvalue problem whose solutions provide the approximate eigenpairs 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\lambda_{i},u_{i}\right)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\nospellcheck off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\xout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none
Let us consider a subspace 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{N}\subset L^{2}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\left(\mathcal{T}\right)$
\end_inset

 with a basis 
\family default
\series default
\shape default
\size default
\emph default
\nospellcheck default
\bar default
\strikeout default
\xout default
\uuline default
\uwave default
\noun default
\color inherit

\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \psi_{j}\left(\boldsymbol{x}\right)\right\} _{j=0}^{N}$
\end_inset

.
 We seek an approximation 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{i,N}\in V_{N}$
\end_inset

 to the eigenfunction 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{i}$
\end_inset

,
 written as a linear combination of the basis functions:
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\nospellcheck off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\xout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none

\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
u_{i,N}=\sum_{j=0}^{N}\overline{u}_{i,j}\psi_{j}.\label{eq:u_approximation}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\family default
\series default
\shape default
\size default
\emph default
\nospellcheck default
\bar default
\strikeout default
\xout default
\uuline default
\uwave default
\noun default
\color inherit
Next we substitute the approximation 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{i,N}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{i}$
\end_inset

 into 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:eigenproblem"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 and apply the Galerkin method.
 This involves testing
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\nospellcheck off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\xout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none
 the resulting expression with the basis functions 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{k}$
\end_inset

 in the Galerkin sense,
 i.e.,
 integrating the residual against 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{k}$
\end_inset

 over the domain 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{T}$
\end_inset

 with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}$
\end_inset

.
 We arrive at the corresponding weak formulation:
 
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\nospellcheck off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\xout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none
multiply both sides by a base function 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{k}$
\end_inset

 and integrate them over interval 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{T}$
\end_inset

 with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}$
\end_inset

,
 we then obtain a weak formulation
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\sum_{j=0}^{N}\overline{u}_{i,j}\intop_{\mathcal{T}}\intop_{\mathcal{T}}\psi_{k}\left(\boldsymbol{y}\right)c\left(\boldsymbol{x},\boldsymbol{y}\right)\psi_{j}\left(\boldsymbol{x}\right)d\boldsymbol{x}d\boldsymbol{y}.=\lambda_{i,N}^{n}\sum_{j=0}^{N}\overline{u}_{i,j}\intop_{\mathcal{T}}\psi_{k}\left(\boldsymbol{x}\right)\psi_{j}\left(\boldsymbol{x}\right)d\boldsymbol{x},\quad\forall k\in\left\{ 0,\ldots,N\right\} ,\label{eq:weak_Galerkin}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\family default
\series default
\shape default
\size default
\emph default
\nospellcheck default
\bar default
\strikeout default
\xout default
\uuline default
\uwave default
\noun default
\color inherit
where 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{i,N}$
\end_inset

 is the approximation of the eigenvalue 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 This can be rewritten in a matrix form.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\boldsymbol{u}}_{i}=\left[\overline{u}_{i,0},\dots,\overline{u}_{i,N}\right]^{T}$
\end_inset

 be the vector representation of the Galerkin approximation 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{i,N}$
\end_inset

.
 Define the matrices 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

 with entries:
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\nospellcheck off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\xout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none

\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A_{k,j}=\intop_{\mathcal{T}}\intop_{\mathcal{T}}\psi_{k}\left(\boldsymbol{y}\right)c\left(\boldsymbol{x},\boldsymbol{y}\right)\psi_{j}\left(\boldsymbol{x}\right)d\boldsymbol{x}d\boldsymbol{y}
\]

\end_inset

and
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
W_{k,j}=\intop_{\mathcal{T}}\psi_{k}\left(\boldsymbol{x}\right)\psi_{j}\left(\boldsymbol{x}\right)d\boldsymbol{x},
\]

\end_inset


\family default
\series default
\shape default
\size default
\emph default
\nospellcheck default
\bar default
\strikeout default
\xout default
\uuline default
\uwave default
\noun default
\color inherit
The weak formulation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:weak_Galerkin"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 then becomes the generalized eigenvalue problem:
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\nospellcheck off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\xout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none

\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
A\overline{\boldsymbol{u}}_{i}=\lambda_{i,N}W\overline{\boldsymbol{u}}_{i}.\label{eq:galerking-eigenvalue-problem}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\family default
\series default
\shape default
\size default
\emph default
\nospellcheck default
\bar default
\strikeout default
\xout default
\uuline default
\uwave default
\noun default
\color inherit
If the kernel 
\begin_inset Formula $c(\boldsymbol{x},\boldsymbol{y})$
\end_inset

 is symmetric and positive semi-definite,
 the matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is symmetric and positive semi-definite.
 The matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

 (the Gram matrix) is symmetric and positive definite since the basis functions 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\psi_{j}\}$
\end_inset

 are linearly independent.
 If the basis functions 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{j}\left(\boldsymbol{x}\right)$
\end_inset

 are orthonormal (i.e.,
 
\begin_inset Formula $W_{kj}=\delta_{kj}$
\end_inset

),
 then 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

 is the identity matrix,
 leaving us with the standard eigenvalue problem 
\begin_inset Formula $A\overline{\boldsymbol{u}}_{i}=\lambda_{i,N}\overline{\boldsymbol{u}}_{i}$
\end_inset

 for the matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The clear choice for basis functions are the orthonormal polynomials with respect to the domain 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{T}$
\end_inset

 (here assumed as multidimensional interval).
 The basis can be then expressed as tensor product of Legendre polynomials,
 whose construction was thoroughly disseminated in Chapter 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "chap:Polynomials"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

,
 specifically Remark 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "rem:affine_generalization_of_Legendre"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 and Remark 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "rem:affine-nodes-and-weights"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Numeric experiments
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We will construct the matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 from the generalized eigenvalue problem 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:galerking-eigenvalue-problem"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
 Our aim is to approximate the entries of the matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 using a series of vector operations,
 i.e.,
 construct all entries 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{k,l}$
\end_inset

 simultaneously.
 This way,
 we will not recompute the values needed to evaluate the integral numerically multiple times.
 Note that this approach will calculate all entries,
 meaning some calculations are redundant since the matrix is symmetric.
 In our code,
 the calculation involves orthonormal Legendre polynomials 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\pi}_{i},i=0,\ldots,N-1$
\end_inset

,
 evaluated at quadrature nodes 
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\nospellcheck off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\xout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none

\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{i},i=1,\ldots,M$
\end_inset


\family default
\series default
\shape default
\size default
\emph default
\nospellcheck default
\bar default
\strikeout default
\xout default
\uuline default
\uwave default
\noun default
\color inherit
,
 and the corresponding quadrature weights 
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\nospellcheck off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\xout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none

\begin_inset Formula $w_{i},i=1,\ldots,M$
\end_inset


\family default
\series default
\shape default
\size default
\emph default
\nospellcheck default
\bar default
\strikeout default
\xout default
\uuline default
\uwave default
\noun default
\color inherit
.
 These vectors will form an 
\begin_inset Formula $M\times N$
\end_inset

 matrix:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\varphi=\left[\begin{array}{cccc}
w_{1}\tilde{\pi}_{0}(\tau_{1}) & w_{2}\tilde{\pi}_{0}(\tau_{2}) & \cdots & w_{M}\tilde{\pi}_{0}(\tau_{M})\\
w_{1}\tilde{\pi}_{1}(\tau_{1}) & w_{2}\tilde{\pi}_{1}(\tau_{2}) & \cdots & w_{M}\tilde{\pi}_{1}(\tau_{M})\\
\vdots & \vdots & \ddots & \vdots\\
w_{1}\tilde{\pi}_{N-1}(\tau_{1}) & w_{2}\tilde{\pi}_{N-1}(\tau_{2}) & \cdots & w_{M}\tilde{\pi}_{N-1}(\tau_{M})
\end{array}\right].
\]

\end_inset

Note that this matrix is formed virtually (not assembled directly) in the code (we use Numpy broadcasting).
 We also define the 
\begin_inset Formula $M\times M$
\end_inset

 covariance matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 whose entries are the values of the covariance function evaluated between pairs of quadrature nodes:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
C=\begin{bmatrix}c\left(\tau_{1},\tau_{1}\right) & c\left(\tau_{1},\tau_{2}\right) & \cdots & c\left(\tau_{1},\tau_{M}\right)\\
c\left(\tau_{2},\tau_{1}\right) & c\left(\tau_{2},\tau_{2}\right) & \cdots & c\left(\tau_{2},\tau_{M}\right)\\
\vdots & \vdots & \ddots & \vdots\\
c\left(\tau_{M},\tau_{1}\right) & c\left(\tau_{M},\tau_{2}\right) & \cdots & c\left(\tau_{M},\tau_{M}\right)
\end{bmatrix},\quad\text{i.e., }C_{ij}=c(\tau_{i},\tau_{j}).
\]

\end_inset

The matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 will then be constructed as:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A=\varphi C\varphi^{T}.
\]

\end_inset

Since we are using orthonormal polynomials as basis functions,
 the matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

 is the identity matrix.
 The eigenvalues and eigenvectors of matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 therefore approximate the eigenvalues 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{i}$
\end_inset

 and the coefficient vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\boldsymbol{u}}_{i}$
\end_inset

 of the eigenfunctions 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{i}$
\end_inset

 in Karhunen-Loève expansion respectively.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This approach is also applicable to higher-dimensional fields.
 One can either:
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Vectorize:
 Unroll the domain (quadrature nodes) and the basis function evaluations into long vectors (e.g.,
 using lexicographical ordering).
 Then,
 construct the large matrices 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

 as in the 1D case and solve the resulting eigenvalue problem.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Use Tensor Operations:
 Treat the operations involved in constructing the matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 (or applying it to a vector) as tensor contractions.
 Tools like `einsum` (e.g.,
 in NumPy) can perform these operations efficiently.
 `einsum` takes multiple input tensors and a string describing which dimensions correspond and how they should be contracted or rearranged to produce the desired output tensor.
 This often avoids forming the large,
 explicit matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 The elements of the tensor 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 are then computed as:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
A_{klij}=\sum_{p=1}^{n}\sum_{q=1}^{n}\sum_{r=1}^{n}\sum_{s=1}^{n}\left(\psi_{k}(x_{p})w_{p}\right)\left(\psi_{l}(x_{q})w_{q}\right)C_{pqrs}\left(\psi_{i}(x_{r})w_{r}\right)\left(\psi_{j}(x_{s})w_{s}\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Eigenvalues-of-cov"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

,
 we see eigenvalues corresponding to different covariance functions;
 in this case,
 they were calculated using 21 orthonormal basis functions.
