\begin_layout Chapter
Conclusion
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "chap:Conclusion"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This thesis set out to implement a numerical method for computing the Karhunen-Loève (KL) expansion of a random field.
 The approach relies on combining the theory of orthogonal polynomials,
 Gaussian quadrature,
 and the Galerkin method to solve the underlying integral eigenvalue problem associated with the random field’s autocovariance function.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We began in Chapter
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "chap:Polynomials"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 by establishing the necessary mathematical tools related to orthogonal polynomials,
 specifically Legendre polynomials.
 This included their definition via weighted inner products,
 their construction using the three-term recurrence relation,
 the connection to Jacobi matrices,
 and the derivation of Gaussian quadrature rules using the Golub-Welsch algorithm.
 The crucial step of adapting these tools to arbitrary finite intervals 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle a,b\rangle$
\end_inset

 was also detailed.
 At the end of Chapter
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "chap:Polynomials"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 provided numerical validation of these concepts,
 demonstrating the generation of polynomials and the efficiency and convergence properties of Gaussian quadrature for various integrands.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Chapter
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "chap:Probability"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 laid the groundwork in probability theory,
 defining concepts such as 
\begin_inset Formula $L^{2}$
\end_inset

 space,
 probability spaces,
 random variables,
 random fields,
 and autocovariance functions,
 with a focus on Gaussian random fields (GRF) which are commonly used in applications.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The core objective was addressed in Chapter
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "chap:Karhunen-Loève-expansion"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

,
 where the Karhunen-Loève theorem was presented.
 We then detailed the Galerkin method for approximating the KL eigenpairs 
\begin_inset Formula $(\lambda_{i},\psi_{i})$
\end_inset

.
 This method utilizes the orthonormal Legendre polynomials from Chapter
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "chap:Polynomials"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 as basis functions and employs Gaussian quadrature rules,
 also from Chapter
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "chap:Polynomials"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

,
 for the efficient calculation of the integrals needed to form the Galerkin matrix system.
 The numerical experiments in this chapter successfully demonstrated the computation of approximate KL eigenvalues and eigenfunctions for selected covariance functions and showed the convergence of the method by analyzing the residual error.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In terms of contribution,
 a significant part of this thesis,
 particularly Chapters
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "chap:Polynomials"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "chap:Probability"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

,
 involved the compilation and concise presentation of established mathematical theory from existing literature 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Gautschi2004,LordPowellShardlow2014"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 These sections aimed to gather the necessary background information in a structured and accessible manner.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The primary practical contribution of this work lies in the implementation and integration of these theoretical components into a working computational pipeline.
 This involved writing and testing code (as evidenced by the results in Chapters
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "chap:Polynomials"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "chap:Karhunen-Loève-expansion"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

) to:
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Generate Legendre polynomials and their recurrence coefficients.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Compute Gaussian quadrature nodes and weights using the Golub-Welsch algorithm.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Assemble the Galerkin matrices using Gaussian quadrature to evaluate the required integrals involving the polynomial basis and the covariance kernel.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Solve the resulting matrix eigenvalue problem to obtain approximate KL eigenpairs.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Visualize and analyze the computed KL components and their accuracy.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Bringing these distinct mathematical tools together to successfully approximate the Karhunen-Loève expansion and demonstrating the process through concrete numerical examples constitutes the core practical achievement of this thesis.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Overall,
 this thesis successfully demonstrated the effectiveness of using orthogonal polynomials and Gaussian quadrature within a Galerkin framework for the numerical approximation of the Karhunen-Loève expansion.
 It provides a practical guide to the underlying theory and its implementation,
 confirming the utility of these combined techniques for computationally representing stochastic processes.
\end_layout

